# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1969-charleston-hospital-strike
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] The **Charleston hospital strike** was a two-month movement in Charleston, South Carolina that protested the unfair and unequal treatment of African American hospital workers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Protests began after twelve black employees were fired for voicing their concerns to the president of Medical College Hospital, which is now the Medical University of South Carolina.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] The strike was one of the last campaigns of the civil rights movement in South Carolina, and the first of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference since the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr. the year before.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Five years after the passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, African Americans in Charleston's Medical College Hospital were still treated more poorly than white employees.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Several African American hospital workers had been attempting to meet with Dr.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] William McCord, the president of the hospital, to discuss low wages, discrimination, and verbal abuse on the job.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] One nurse, Mary Grimes-Vanderhorst, claimed that she was unjustly demoted from a nurse to a nursing assistant because of her race, consequentially reducing her pay.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Other African American nurses and hospital workers stated that they were being paid less than white employees who did the same work, receiving $1.30 per hour, 30¢ below the minimum wage.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Black employees often complained that racial slurs and racist comments had been used against them and that the hospital had taken no action to discipline employees who made such comments.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Some African American workers were prohibited from eating their lunch in break rooms because of segregation, and were forced to eat outside or in boiler rooms.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] In September 1968, some hospital workers contacted Local 1199, a national health care workers' union.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Local 1199 agreed to establish a chapter in Charleston, named Local 1199B, with Mary Moultrie as its president.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Moultrie was also an employee of the hospital.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] The Local 1199B union, with assistance from the Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC), requested formal recognition from the hospital's president, which was rejected.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] On March 18, 1969, President McCord agreed to meet with Moultrie and several other employees during their lunch break.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] But McCord brought an anti-union delegation outnumbering Moultrie’s group.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Moultrie and her colleagues walked out of the meeting knowing that compromise would not be possible with the anti-union delegation's presence.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Moultrie and eleven other workers briefly took over the president’s office in protest.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] The twelve workers were accused of leaving their patients unattended and were terminated that day.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] However, according to Louise Brown, one of the African American women who was fired, the twelve workers were on their lunch break; their patients, as usual, were already covered by other hospital staff.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] In response to the firing of the twelve African American employees, on March 19, 1969, over sixty African American hospital employees walked off of their jobs and led a strike against the hospital.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Both hospital employers, the State of South Carolina and Charleston County, committed to using any means at their disposal to avoid unionization.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Within a few hours of the beginning of the strike, the Medical College prohibited all picketing, which was later amended to require picketers to stand no fewer than twenty yards apart.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] McNair feared that the strike would lead to more strikes in other fields of work around the state.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] On April 25, 1969, Governor McNair ordered over 1,000 state troopers and National Guardsmen, imposed a 9 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew, and declared a state of emergency.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Some protesters defied the curfew and led the strike into the night.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] By early summer, armored personnel carriers and soldiers with fixed-bayonets had arrived in the city.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Violence increased against strikers: one union member's hotel room was firebombed and mysterious fires erupted around the city.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Mary Moultrie moved out of her home for her family’s safety and slept on a cot at the union hall under the guard of armed youths.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] William Bill Saunders, a Korean War veteran who participated in the strike, observed that police arrested dozens of people daily.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Over 1,000 people were arrested throughout the civil conflict.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] By the end of April, the movement gathered the support of Coretta Scott King and SCLC members Andrew Young and Ralph Abernathy.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] The following week on Mother's Day, over ten thousand people, including five U.S.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Congressmen, marched in downtown Charleston.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] The tourist industry of Charleston was strained as a result of these marches as protesters clogged public streets and markets.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Local 1199B created advertisements that sought to encourage locals to purchase only food and medicine to further disrupt the city's economy.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Most politicians in South Carolina agreed with Governor McNair's response to the strike, though his constituents grew increasingly frustrated by the ongoing fallout.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Many businesses in Charleston were negatively affected by the strikes, both by strikers blocking establishments and the imposed 9 p.m. curfew.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Some businesses reported revenue reductions by as much as 50%, including the Holiday Inn and other hotels that were forced to cancel events and conferences.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Additionally, the South Carolina Task Force for Community Uplift noted that the use of national guard forces required $10,000 daily (approximately $71,000 in 2020 dollars).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] A federal investigation charged the Medical College Hospital with 37 instances of civil rights violation and threatened to cut off $12 million in federal funding.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] President McCord yielded, and on June 27, 1969, he announced that a settlement had been made between the hospital and the strikers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] The Medical College Hospital promised to rehire strikers the following week, including the original twelve employees who had been fired, and to abide by a newly established six-step grievance process, and to provide modest pay increases.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Though the union was never formally recognized by the Hospital or by any level of government, the strike was considered a success.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Consequently, African Americans at the Medical College received higher pay and a more transparent system of hiring.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] Within a few months of the strike's end, Local 1199 withdrew its support from Charleston after failing to secure legal recognition.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] The 1970 political documentary *I Am Somebody*, directed by Madeline Anderson, highlighted the Charleston strikes on a national level.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] On August 15, 1969, two hundred black Charleston city sanitation workers led a similar strike to protest and demanded better wages and improved working conditions.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/1969-charleston-hospital-strike] After two months, the strike was resolved with a compromise.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] African-American history began in the 16th century, when mainly West African and Central African slave traders sold African artisans, farmers, and warriors to European slave traders, who transported them across the Atlantic to the Western Hemisphere.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] They were sold as slaves to European colonists and put to work on plantations, particularly in the southern colonies.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] A few were able to achieve freedom through manumission or escape, and founded independent communities before and during the American Revolution.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] After the United States was founded in 1783, most American Black people continued to be enslaved, primarily in the American South, with four million enslaved people only liberated after the Northern victory over the South in the Civil War of 1861 to 1865.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] During Reconstruction, African Americans gained citizenship and adult-males the right to vote; however, due to widespread belief in White supremacy, they were treated as second-class citizens and soon effectively disenfranchised in the South.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] These circumstances changed due to participation in the military conflicts of the United States, substantial migration out of the South, the elimination of legal racial segregation, and the civil rights movement which sought political and social freedom.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] However, racism against African Americans and racial socioeconomic disparity remain a problem into the 21st century.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In the 20th and 21st centuries, immigration has played an increasingly significant role in the African-American community.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Black population were immigrants, and 20% were either immigrants or the children of immigrants.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] While some Black immigrants or their children may also come to identify as African American, the majority of first-generation immigrants do not, preferring to identify with their nation of origin.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Most African Americans are of West African and coastal Central African ancestry, with varying amounts of Western European and Native American ancestry (see §Genetics).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] African-American culture has had a significant influence on worldwide culture, making numerous contributions to the English language, literature, politics, cuisine, sports, and music.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The African-American contribution to popular music is so profound that most American popular music, including gospel, blues, jazz, rock and roll, R&B, soul, funk, disco, hip-hop, and house has its origins either partially or entirely in the African-American community.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The vast majority of those who were enslaved and transported in the transatlantic slave trade were people from several Central and West African ethnic groups.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] They had been captured directly by European slave traders in coastal raids, or captured and sold by West African slave traders or by half-European "merchant princes" to European slave traders, who brought them to the Americas.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The first African slaves in what is now the United States arrived in the early 16th century.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Africans were among Juan Ponce de León's 1513 voyage that landed in what would become Spanish Florida, and enslaved Africans arrived around the same time to Spanish Puerto Rico.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Africans also came via Santo Domingo in the Caribbean to the San Miguel de Gualdape colony (most likely located in the Winyah Bay area of present-day South Carolina), founded by Spanish explorer Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón in 1526.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The ill-fated colony was almost immediately disrupted by a fight over leadership, during which the slaves revolted and fled the colony to seek refuge among local Native Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] De Ayllón and many of the colonists died shortly afterward, due to an epidemic and the colony was abandoned.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The settlers and the slaves who had not escaped returned to the Island of Hispaniola, whence they had come.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The enslaved explorer Esteban arrived in Florida with the Narváez expedition in 1528, a journey that first landed in Santo Domingo and later traveled into Spanish Texas and the Southwest before ending in Mexico.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The marriage between Luisa de Abrego, a free Black domestic servant from Seville, and Miguel Rodríguez, a White Segovian conquistador in 1565 in St.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Augustine (Spanish Florida), is the first known and recorded Christian marriage anywhere in what is now the continental United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The first recorded Africans in English America (including most of the future United States) were "20 and odd negroes" who arrived in Jamestown, Virginia via Cape Comfort in August 1619 as indentured servants.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] As many Virginian settlers began to die from harsh conditions, more and more Africans were brought to work as laborers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] An indentured servant (who could be White or Black) would work for several years (usually four to seven) without wages.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The status of indentured servants in early Virginia and Maryland was similar to slavery.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Servants could be bought, sold, or leased, and they could be physically beaten for disobedience or attempting to running away.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Unlike slaves, they were freed after their term of service expired or if their freedom was purchased.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Their children did not inherit their status, and on their release from contract they received "a year's provision of corn, double apparel, tools necessary", and a small cash payment called "freedom dues".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Africans could legally raise crops and cattle to purchase their freedom.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] They raised families, married other Africans and sometimes intermarried with Native Americans or European settlers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] By the 1640s and 1650s, several African families owned farms around Jamestown, and some became wealthy by colonial standards and purchased indentured servants of their own.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 1640, the Virginia General Court recorded the earliest documentation of lifetime slavery when they sentenced John Punch, a Negro, to lifetime servitude under his master Hugh Gwyn, for running away.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In Spanish Florida, some Spanish married or had unions with Pensacola, Creek or African women, both enslaved and free, and their descendants created a mixed-race population of mestizos and mulattos.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The Spanish encouraged slaves from the colony of Georgia to come to Florida as a refuge, promising freedom in exchange for conversion to Catholicism.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] King Charles II issued a royal proclamation freeing all slaves who fled to Spanish Florida and accepted conversion and baptism.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Augustine, but escaped slaves also reached Pensacola.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Augustine had mustered an all-Black militia unit defending Spanish Florida as early as 1683.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] One of the Dutch African arrivals, Anthony Johnson, would later own one of the first Black "slaves", John Casor, resulting from the court ruling of a civil case.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The popular conception of a race-based slave system did not fully develop until the 18th century.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The Dutch West India Company introduced slavery in 1625 with the importation of eleven Black slaves into New Amsterdam (present-day New York City).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] All the colony's slaves, however, were freed upon its surrender to the English.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Massachusetts was the first English colony to legally recognize slavery in 1641.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 1662, Virginia passed a law that children of enslaved women would take the status of the mother, rather than that of the father, as was the case under common law.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] This legal principle was called *partus sequitur ventrum*.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] By an act of 1699, Virginia ordered the deportation of all free Blacks, effectively defining all people of African descent who remained in the colony as slaves.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 1670, the colonial assembly passed a law prohibiting free and baptized Blacks (and Native Americans) from purchasing Christians (in this act meaning White Europeans) but allowing them to buy people "of their owne nation".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In Spanish Louisiana, although there was no movement toward abolition of the African slave trade, Spanish rule introduced a new law called *coartación*, which allowed slaves to buy their freedom, and that of others.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Although some did not have the money to do so, government measures on slavery enabled the existence of many free Blacks.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] This caused problems to the Spaniards with the French creoles (French who had settled in New France) who had also populated Spanish Louisiana.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The French creoles cited that measure as one of the system's worst elements.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] First established in South Carolina in 1704, groups of armed White men—slave patrols—were formed to monitor enslaved Black people.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Their function was to police slaves, especially fugitives.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Slave owners feared that slaves might organize revolts or slave rebellions, so state militias were formed to provide a military command structure and discipline within the slave patrols.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] These patrols were used to detect, encounter, and crush any organized slave meetings which might lead to revolts or rebellions.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The earliest African American congregations and churches were organized before 1800 in both northern and southern cities following the Great Awakening.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] By 1775, Africans made up 20% of the population in the American colonies, which made them the second-largest ethnic group after English Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] During the 1770s, Africans, both enslaved and free, helped rebellious American colonists secure their independence by defeating the British in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Blacks played a role in both sides in the American Revolution.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Activists in the Patriot cause included James Armistead, Prince Whipple, and Oliver Cromwell.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Around 15,000 Black Loyalists left with the British after the war, most of them ending up as free Black people in England or its colonies, such as the Black Nova Scotians and the Sierra Leone Creole people.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In the Spanish Louisiana, Governor Bernardo de Gálvez organized Spanish free Black men into two militia companies to defend New Orleans during the American Revolution.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] They fought in the 1779 battle in which Spain captured Baton Rouge from the British.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Gálvez also commanded them in campaigns against the British outposts in Mobile, Alabama, and Pensacola, Florida.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] He recruited slaves for the militia by pledging to free anyone who was seriously wounded and promised to secure a low price for *coartación* (buy their freedom and that of others) for those who received lesser wounds.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] During the 1790s, Governor Francisco Luis Héctor, baron of Carondelet reinforced local fortifications and recruit even more free Black men for the militia.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Carondelet doubled the number of free Black men who served, creating two more militia companies—one made up of Black members and the other of pardo (mixed race).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Serving in the militia brought free Black men one step closer to equality with Whites, allowing them, for example, the right to carry arms and boosting their earning power.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] However, actually these privileges distanced free Black men from enslaved Blacks and encouraged them to identify with Whites.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Slavery had been tacitly enshrined in the US Constitution through provisions such as Article I, Section 2, Clause 3, commonly known as the 3/5 compromise.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Due to the restrictions of Section 9, Clause 1, Congress was unable to pass an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves until 1807.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Fugitive slave laws (derived from the Fugitive Slave Clause of the Constitution—Article IV, Section 2, Clause 3) were passed by Congress in both 1793 and 1850, guaranteeing the right of a slaveholder to recover an escaped slave anywhere within the US.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Slave owners, who viewed enslaved people as property, ensured that it became a federal crime to aid or assist those who had fled slavery or to interfere with their capture.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] By that time, slavery, which almost exclusively targeted Black people, had become the most critical and contentious political issue in the Antebellum United States, repeatedly sparking crises and conflicts.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Among these were the Missouri Compromise, the Compromise of 1850, the infamous Dred Scott decision, and John Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Prior to the Civil War, eight serving presidents had owned slaves, a practice that was legally protected under the US Constitution.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] By 1860, the number of enslaved Black people in the US had grown to between 3.5 and 4.4 million, largely as a result of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In addition, 488,000–500,000 Black people lived free around the country, with legislated limits imposed upon them in addition to "unconquerable prejudice" from Whites according to Henry Clay.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In response to these conditions, some free Black people chose to leave the US and emigrate to Liberia in West Africa.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Liberia had been established in 1821 as a settlement by the American Colonization Society (ACS), with many abolitionist members of the ACS believing Black Americans would have greater opportunities for freedom and equality in Africa than they would in the US.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Slaves not only represented a significant financial investment for their owners, but they also played a crucial role in producing the country's most valuable product and export: cotton.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Enslaved people were instrumental in the construction of several prominent structures such as, the United States Capitol, the White House and other Washington, D.C.–based buildings.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Similar building projects existed in the slave states.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] By 1815, the domestic slave trade had become a significant and major economic activity in the United States, continuing to flourish until the 1860s.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Historians estimate that nearly one million individuals were subjected to this forced migration, which was often referred to as a new "Middle Passage".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The historian Ira Berlin described this internal forced migration of enslaved people as the "central event" in the life of a slave during the period between the American Revolution and the Civil War.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Berlin emphasized that whether enslaved individuals were directly uprooted or lived in constant fear that they or their families would be involuntarily relocated, "the massive deportation traumatized Black people" throughout the US.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] As a result of this large-scale forced movement, countless individuals lost their connection to families and clans, and many ethnic Africans lost their knowledge of varying tribal origins in Africa.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Emigration of free Blacks to their continent of origin had been proposed since the Revolutionary war.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] After Haiti became independent, it tried to recruit African Americans to migrate there after it re-established trade relations with the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The Haitian Union was a group formed to promote relations between the countries.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] After riots against Blacks in Cincinnati, its Black community sponsored founding of the Wilberforce Colony, an initially successful settlement of African American immigrants to Canada.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The colony was one of the first such independent political entities.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] It lasted for a number of decades and provided a destination for about 200 Black families emigrating from a number of locations in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 1863, during the American Civil War, President Abraham Lincoln signed the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The proclamation declared that all slaves in Confederate-held territory were free.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Advancing Union troops enforced the proclamation, with Texas being the last state to be emancipated, in 1865.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Slavery in a few border states continued until the ratification of the Thirteenth Amendment in December 1865.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] While the Naturalization Act of 1790 limited US citizenship to Whites only, the 14th Amendment (1868) gave Black people citizenship, and the 15th Amendment (1870) gave Black men the right to vote.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] African Americans quickly set up congregations for themselves, as well as schools and community/civic associations, to have space away from White control or oversight.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] While the post-war Reconstruction era was initially a time of progress for African Americans, that period ended in 1876.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] By the late 1890s, Southern states enacted Jim Crow laws to enforce racial segregation and disenfranchisement.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Segregation was now imposed with Jim Crow laws, using signs used to show Blacks where they could legally walk, talk, drink, rest, or eat.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] For those places that were racially mixed, non-Whites had to wait until all White customers were dealt with.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Most African Americans obeyed the Jim Crow laws, to avoid racially motivated violence.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] To maintain self-esteem and dignity, African Americans such as Anthony Overton and Mary McLeod Bethune continued to build their own schools, churches, banks, social clubs, and other businesses.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In the last decade of the 19th century, racially discriminatory laws and racial violence aimed at African Americans began to mushroom in the United States, a period often referred to as the "nadir of American race relations".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] These discriminatory acts included racial segregation—upheld by the United States Supreme Court decision in *Plessy v.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The desperate conditions of African Americans in the South sparked the Great Migration during the first half of the 20th century which led to a growing African American community in Northern and Western United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The rapid influx of Blacks disturbed the racial balance within Northern and Western cities, exacerbating hostility between both Blacks and Whites in the two regions.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The Red Summer of 1919 was marked by hundreds of deaths and higher casualties across the US as a result of race riots that occurred in more than three dozen cities, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919 and the Omaha race riot of 1919.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Overall, Blacks in Northern and Western cities experienced systemic discrimination in a plethora of aspects of life.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Within employment, economic opportunities for Blacks were routed to the lowest-status and restrictive in potential mobility.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] While many Whites defended their space with violence, intimidation, or legal tactics toward African Americans, many other Whites migrated to more racially homogeneous suburban or exurban regions, a process known as White flight.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Despite discrimination, drawing cards for leaving the hopelessness in the South were the growth of African American institutions and communities in Northern cities.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Institutions included Black oriented organizations (e.g., Urban League, NAACP), churches, businesses, and newspapers, as well as successes in the development in African American intellectual culture, music, and popular culture (e.g., Harlem Renaissance, Chicago Black Renaissance).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The Cotton Club in Harlem was a Whites-only establishment, with Blacks (such as Duke Ellington) allowed to perform, but to a White audience.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Black Americans also found a new ground for political power in Northern cities, without the enforced disabilities of Jim Crow.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] By the 1950s, the civil rights movement was gaining momentum.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] A 1955 lynching that sparked public outrage about injustice was that of Emmett Till, a 14-year-old boy from Chicago.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Spending the summer with relatives in Money, Mississippi, Till was killed for allegedly having wolf-whistled at a White woman.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Till had been badly beaten, one of his eyes was gouged out, and he was shot in the head.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The visceral response to his mother's decision to have an open-casket funeral mobilized the Black community throughout the US.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Vann Newkirk wrote "the trial of his killers became a pageant illuminating the tyranny of White supremacy".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The state of Mississippi tried two defendants, but they were speedily acquitted by an all-White jury.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom and the conditions which brought it into being are credited with putting pressure on presidents John F.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] By 1966, the emergence of the Black Power movement, which lasted from 1966 to 1975, expanded upon the aims of the civil rights movement to include economic and political self-sufficiency, and freedom from White authority.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] During the post-war period, many African Americans continued to be economically disadvantaged relative to other Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Average Black income stood at 54 percent of that of White workers in 1947, and 55 percent in 1962.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 1965, 43 percent of all Black families fell into the poverty bracket, earning under $3,000 (equivalent to $30,649 in 2025) a year.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] The 1960s saw improvements in the social and economic conditions of many Black Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] From 1965 to 1969, Black family income rose from 54 to 60 percent of White family income.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 1968, 23 percent of Black families earned under $3,000 (equivalent to $27,775 in 2025) a year, compared with 41 percent in 1960.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 1965, 19 percent of Black Americans had incomes equal to the national median, a proportion that rose to 27 percent by 1967.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 1960, the median level of education for Blacks had been 10.8 years, and by the late 1960s, the figure rose to 12.2 years, half a year behind the median for Whites.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Politically and economically, African Americans have made substantial strides during the post–civil rights era.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 1967, Thurgood Marshall became the first African American Supreme Court Justice.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 1968, Shirley Chisholm became the first Black woman elected to the US Congress.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 1989, Douglas Wilder became the first African American elected governor in US history.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Clarence Thomas succeeded Marshall to become the second African American Supreme Court Justice in 1991.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 1992, Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois became the first African American woman elected to the US Senate.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] There were 8,936 Black officeholders in the United States in 2000, showing a net increase of 7,467 since 1970.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 2005, the number of Africans immigrating to the United States, in a single year, surpassed the peak number who were involuntarily brought to the United States during the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] On November 4, 2008, Democratic Senator Barack Obama—the son of a White American mother and a Kenyan father—defeated Republican Senator John McCain to become the first African American to be elected president.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] At least 95 percent of African American voters voted for Obama.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] He also received overwhelming support from young and educated Whites, a majority of Asians, and Hispanics, picking up a number of new states in the Democratic electoral column.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Obama lost the overall White vote, although he won a larger proportion of White votes than any previous non-incumbent Democratic presidential candidate since Jimmy Carter.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] Obama was reelected for a second and final term, by a similar margin on November 6, 2012.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In 2021, Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican father and Indian mother, became the first woman, the first African American, and the first Asian American to serve as Vice President of the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p01] In June 2021, Juneteenth, a day which commemorates the end of slavery in the US, became a federal holiday.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 1790, when the first US census was taken, Africans (including slaves and free people) numbered about 760,000—about 19.3% of the population.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 1860, at the start of the Civil War, the African American population had increased to 4.4 million, but the percentage rate dropped to 14% of the overall population of the country.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The vast majority were slaves, with only 488,000 counted as "freemen".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] By 1900, the Black population had doubled and reached 8.8 million.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 1910, about 90% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Large numbers began migrating north looking for better job opportunities and living conditions, and to escape Jim Crow laws and racial violence.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The Great Migration, as it was called, spanned the 1890s to the 1970s.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] From 1916 through the 1960s, more than six million Black people moved north.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] But in the 1970s and 1980s, that trend reversed, with more African Americans moving south to the Sun Belt than leaving it.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] By 1990, the African American population reached about 30 million and represented 12% of the US population, roughly the same proportion as in 1900.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] At the time of the 2000 US census, 54.8% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In that year, 17.6% of African Americans lived in the Northeast and 18.7% in the Midwest, while only 8.9% lived in the Western states.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The west does have a sizable Black population in certain areas, however.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] California, the nation's most populous state, has the fifth-largest African American population, only behind New York, Texas, Georgia, and Florida.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] According to the 2000 census, approximately 2.05% of African Americans identified as Hispanic or Latino in origin, many of whom may be of Brazilian, Puerto Rican, Dominican, Cuban, Haitian, or other Latin American descent.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The only self-reported *ancestral* groups larger than African Americans are the Irish and Germans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] According to the 2010 census, nearly 3% of people who self-identified as Black had recent ancestors who immigrated from another country.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Self-reported non-Hispanic Black immigrants from the Caribbean, mostly from Jamaica and Haiti, represented 0.9% of the US population, at 2.6 million.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants from sub-Saharan Africa also represented 0.9%, at about 2.8 million.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Additionally, self-identified Black Hispanics represented 0.4% of the United States population, at about 1.2 million people, largely found within the Puerto Rican and Dominican communities.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants hailing from other countries in the Americas, such as Brazil and Canada, as well as several European countries, represented less than 0.1% of the population.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Mixed-race Hispanic and non-Hispanic Americans who identified as being part Black, represented 0.9% of the population.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Of the 12.6% of United States residents who identified as Black, around 10.3% were "native Black American" or ethnic African Americans, who are direct descendants of West/Central Africans brought to the US as slaves.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] These individuals make up well over 80% of all Blacks in the country.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] When including people of mixed-race origin, about 13.5% of the US population self-identified as Black or "mixed with Black".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] However, according to the US Census Bureau, evidence from the 2000 census indicates that many African and Caribbean immigrant ethnic groups do not identify as "Black, African Am., or Negro".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Instead, they wrote in their own respective ethnic groups in the "Some Other Race" write-in entry.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] As a result, the census bureau devised a new, separate "African American" ethnic group category in 2010 for ethnic African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Nigerian Americans and Ethiopian Americans were the most reported sub-Saharan African groups in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In the 2020 census, the African American population was undercounted at an estimated rate of 3.3%, up from 2.1% in 2010.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Texas has the largest African American population by state with approximately four million.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Followed by Texas is Florida, with 3.8 million, and Georgia, with 3.6 million.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Mississippi is the state with the highest African American share of the population at 39%.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Followed by Mississippi is Louisiana at 34%, and Georgia at 32%.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] After 100 years of African Americans leaving the south in large numbers seeking better opportunities and treatment in the west and north, a movement known as the Great Migration, there is now a reverse trend, called the New Great Migration.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] As with the earlier Great Migration, the New Great Migration is primarily directed toward cities and large urban areas, such as Charlotte, Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, Huntsville, Raleigh, Tampa, San Antonio, New Orleans, Memphis, Nashville, Jacksonville, and so forth.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] A growing percentage of African Americans from the west and north are migrating to the southern region of the US for economic and cultural reasons.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2020, New York City, Chicago, and Los Angeles metropolitan areas had the highest decline in African Americans, while Atlanta, Dallas, and Houston had the highest increase respectively.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Despite recent declines, as of 2020, the New York City metropolitan area still has the largest African American metropolitan population in the United States and the only to have over three million African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Among cities of 100,000 or more, South Fulton, Georgia had the highest percentage of Black residents of any large US city in 2020, with 93%.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Claiborne County, Mississippi is the Blackest county in the U.S. at 87% Black in 2020.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Cook County, Illinois has the largest Black population in the U.S. with 1,185,601 Black residents in 2020.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The nation's most affluent community with an African American majority resides in View Park–Windsor Hills, California, with an annual median household income of $159,618 and median home price of about $1.5 million in 2025.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Additionally, there is a significant affluent Black presence in the southern Chicago suburbs of Cook County, Illinois.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2006, Queens County, New York was the only county with a population of 65,000 or more where African Americans had a higher median household income than White Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Seatack, Virginia is currently the oldest African American community in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] It survives today with a vibrant and active civic community.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] During slavery, anti-literacy laws were enacted in the US that prohibited education for Black people.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Slave owners saw literacy as a threat to the institution of slavery.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] When slavery was finally abolished in 1865, public educational systems were expanding across the country.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] By 1870, around seventy-four institutions in the south provided a form of advanced education for African American students.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] By 1900, over a hundred programs at these schools provided training for Black professionals, including teachers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Many of the students at Fisk University, including the young W.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Du Bois, taught school during the summers to support their studies.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African Americans were very concerned to provide quality education for their children, but White supremacy limited their ability to participate in educational policymaking on the political level.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] State governments soon moved to undermine their citizenship by restricting their right to vote.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] By the late 1870s, Blacks were disenfranchised and segregated across the American South.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] White politicians in Mississippi and other states withheld financial resources and supplies from Black schools.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Nevertheless, the presence of Black teachers, and their engagement with their communities both inside and outside the classroom, ensured that Black students had access to education despite these external constraints.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] During World War II, demands for unity and racial tolerance on the home front provided an opening for the first Black history curriculum in the country.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] For example, during the early 1940s, Madeline Morgan, a Black teacher in the Chicago public schools, created a curriculum for students in grades one through eight highlighting the contributions of Black people to the history of the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] At the close of the war, Chicago's Board of Education downgraded the curriculum's status from mandatory to optional.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Predominantly Black schools for kindergarten through twelfth grade students were common throughout the US before the 1970s.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] By 1972, however, desegregation efforts meant that only 25% of Black students were in schools with more than 90% non-White students.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] However, since then, a trend towards re-segregation affected communities across the country: by 2011, 2.9 million African American students were in such overwhelmingly minority schools, including 53% of Black students in school districts that were formerly under desegregation orders.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] As late as 1947, about one third of African Americans over 65 were considered to lack the literacy to read and write their own names.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] By 1969, illiteracy as it had been traditionally defined, had been largely eradicated among younger African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Between 1995 and 2009, freshmen college enrollment for African Americans increased by 73 percent and only 15 percent for Whites.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Black women are enrolled in college more than any other race and gender group, leading all with 9.7% enrolled according to the 2011 US census.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The average high school graduation rate of Blacks in the United States has steadily increased to 71% in 2013.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Separating this statistic into component parts shows it varies greatly depending upon the state and the school district examined.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] 38% of Black males graduated in the state of New York but in Maine 97% graduated and exceeded the White male graduation rate by 11 percentage points.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In much of the southeastern United States and some parts of the southwestern United States the graduation rate of White males was in fact below 70% such as in Florida where 62% of White males graduated from high school.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Examining specific school districts paints an even more complex picture.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In the Detroit school district, the graduation rate of Black males was 20% but 7% for White males.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In the New York City school district 28% of Black males graduate from high school compared to 57% of White males.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In Newark County 76% of Black males graduated compared to 67% for White males.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Further academic improvement has occurred in 2015.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Roughly 23% of all Blacks have bachelor's degrees.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 1988, 21% of Whites had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 11% of Blacks.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2015, 23% of Blacks had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 36% of Whites.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Foreign born Blacks, 9% of the Black population, made even greater strides.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] They exceed native born Blacks by 10 percentage points.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] College Board, which runs the official college-level advanced placement (AP) programs in American high schools, have has received criticism in recent years that its curricula have focused too much on Euro-centric history.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2020, College Board reshaped some curricula among history-based courses to further reflect the African diaspora.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2021, College Board announced it would be piloting an AP African American Studies course between 2022 and 2024.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The course officially launched in August 2024.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In June 2023, the Supreme Court ended race-based affirmative action at American colleges and universities.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In response, many of the nation's most prominent historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs) have reported a significant surge in applications and enrollment.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Slightly more than 250,000 African American students in the high school graduating class of 2025 took the Scholastic Aptitude Test (SAT) making up 13% of test takers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African American students had an average score of 904 which is lower than the national average of 1,209.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Asian American students had the highest average with 1,229.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] According to a 2025 study, African Americans have the highest average student debt.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African Americans with bachelor's degrees owe an average of $52,726 in student loans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Nearly 70% of African Americans took out a loan to fund their undergraduate education.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African American women, in particular, carry the highest average student debt in the nation.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs), which were founded when segregated institutions of higher learning did not admit African Americans, continue to thrive and educate students of all races today.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] There are 107 HBCUs representing three percent of the nation's colleges and universities with the majority established in the Southeast.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] HBCUs have been largely responsible for establishing and expanding the African American middle-class by providing more career opportunities for African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The economic disparity between the races in the US has marginally improved since the end of slavery.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 1863, two years prior to emancipation, Black people owned 0.5 percent of the national wealth, while in 2019 it is just over 1.5 percent.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Racial disparity in poverty rates has narrowed since the civil rights era, with the poverty rate among African Americans decreasing from 24.7% in 2004 to 18.8% in 2020, compared to 10.5% for all Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Poverty is associated with higher rates of marital stress and dissolution, physical and mental health problems, disability, cognitive deficits, low educational attainment, and crime.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African Americans have a long and diverse history of business ownership.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Although the first African American business is unknown, slaves captured from West Africa are believed to have established commercial enterprises as peddlers and skilled craftspeople as far back as the 17th century.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Washington became the most famous proponent of African American businesses.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] DuBois also commended business as a vehicle for African American advancement.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2002, African American-owned businesses accounted for 1.2 million of the US's 23 million businesses.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] As of 2011, African American-owned businesses account for approximately two million US businesses.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Black-owned businesses experienced the largest growth in number of businesses among minorities from 2002 to 2011.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Twenty-five percent of Blacks had white-collar occupations (management, professional, and related fields) in 2000, compared with 33.6% of Americans overall.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2001, over half of African American households of married couples earned $50,000 or more.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Although in the same year African Americans were over-represented among the nation's poor, this was directly related to the disproportionate percentage of African American families headed by single women; such families are collectively poorer, regardless of ethnicity.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2006, the median earnings of African American men was more than Black and non-Black American women overall, and in all educational levels.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] At the same time, among American men, income disparities were significant; the median income of African American men was approximately 76 cents for every dollar of their European American counterparts, although the gap narrowed somewhat with a rise in educational level.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Overall, the median earnings of African American men were 72 cents for every dollar earned of their Asian American counterparts, and $1.17 for every dollar earned by Hispanic men.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] On the other hand, by 2006, among American women with post-secondary education, African American women have made significant advances; the median income of African American women was more than those of their Asian-, European- and Hispanic American counterparts with at least some college education.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The US public sector is the single most important source of employment for African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] During 2008–2010, 21.2% of all Black workers were public employees, compared with 16.3% of non-Black workers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Both before and after the onset of the Great Recession, African Americans were 30% more likely than other workers to be employed in the public sector.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The public sector is also a critical source of decent-paying jobs for Black Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] For both men and women, the median wage earned by Black employees is significantly higher in the public sector than in other industries.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 1999, the median income of African American families was $33,255 compared to $53,356 of European Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In times of economic hardship for the nation, African Americans suffer disproportionately from job loss and underemployment, with the Black underclass being hardest hit.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The phrase "last hired and first fired" is reflected in the Bureau of Labor Statistics unemployment figures.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Nationwide, the October 2008 unemployment rate for African Americans was 11.1%, while the nationwide rate was 6.5%.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2007, the average income for African Americans was approximately $34,000, compared to $55,000 for Whites.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African Americans experience a higher rate of unemployment than the general population.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The income gap between Black and White families is also significant.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2005, employed Blacks earned 65% of the wages of Whites, down from 82% in 1975.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] *The New York Times* reported in 2006 that in Queens, New York, the median income among African American families exceeded that of White families, which the newspaper attributed to the growth in the number of two-parent Black families.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] It noted that Queens was the only county with more than 65,000 residents where that was true.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2011, it was reported that 72% of Black babies were born to unwed mothers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The poverty rate among single-parent Black families was 39.5% in 2005, according to Walter E.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Williams, while it was 9.9% among married-couple Black families.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Among White families, the respective rates were 26.4% and 6% in poverty.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Collectively, African Americans are more involved in the American political process than other minority groups in the United States, indicated by the highest level of voter registration and participation in elections among these groups in 2004.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African Americans also have the highest level of Congressional representation of any minority group in the US.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Homeownership in the US is the strongest indicator of financial stability and the primary asset most Americans use to generate wealth.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African Americans continue to lag behind other racial groups in homeownership.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In the first quarter of 2021, 45.1% of African Americans owned their homes, compared to 65.3% of all Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The African American homeownership rate has remained relatively flat since the 1970s despite an increase in anti-discrimination housing laws and protections.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The African American homeownership rate peaked in 2004 at 49.7%.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The average White high school drop-out still has a slightly better chance of owning a home than the average African American college graduate usually due to unfavorable debt-to-income ratios or credit scores among most African American college graduates.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Since 2000, fast-growing housing costs in most cities have made it even more difficult for the US African American homeownership rate to significantly grow and reach over 50% for the first time in history.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] From 2000 to 2022, the median home price in the US grew 160%, outpacing average annual household income growth in that same period, which only grew about 30%.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] South Carolina is the state with the most African American homeownership, with about 55% of African Americans owning their own homes.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Black people, who make up 12% of the total U.S. population, make up 32% of all people experiencing homelessness, according to the data.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Since the mid 20th century, a large majority of African Americans support the Democratic Party.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In the 2024 Presidential election, 86% of African American voters supported Democrat Kamala Harris, while 13% supported Republican Donald Trump.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Although there is an African American lobby in foreign policy, it has not had the impact that African American organizations have had in domestic policy.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Many African Americans were excluded from electoral politics in the decades following the end of Reconstruction.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The African American trend of voting for Democrats can be traced back to the 1930s during the Great Depression, when Franklin D.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal program provided economic relief to African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal coalition turned the Democratic Party into an organization of the working class and their liberal allies, regardless of region.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The African American vote became even more solidly Democratic when Democratic presidents John F.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Johnson pushed for civil rights legislation during the 1960s.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 1960, nearly a third of African Americans voted for Republican Richard Nixon.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Conservatism has been growing among African Americans, particularly since the 2020 Presidential election.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In the 2024 election, Trump secured a slightly larger share of the African American vote compared to his 2020 performance.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] "Lift Every Voice and Sing" is often referred to as the Black national anthem in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 1919, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) had dubbed it the "Negro national anthem" for its power in voicing a cry for liberation and affirmation for African-American people.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The majority of African Americans are Protestant, many of whom follow the historically Black churches.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The term Black church refers to churches which minister to predominantly African American congregations.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Black congregations were first established by freed slaves at the end of the 17th century, and later when slavery was abolished more African Americans were allowed to create a unique form of Christianity that was culturally influenced by African spiritual traditions.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] According to a 2007 survey, more than half of the African American population are part of the historically Black churches.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The largest Protestant denomination among African Americans is the Baptists, distributed mainly in four denominations, the largest being the National Baptist Convention, USA and the National Baptist Convention of America.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The second-largest is the Methodists, the largest organizations of which are the African Methodist Episcopal Church and the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Pentecostals are distributed among several different religious bodies, with the Church of God in Christ as the largest among them by far.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] About 16% of African American Christians are members of White Protestant communions; these denominations (which include the United Church of Christ) mostly have a 2–3% African American membership.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] There are also large numbers of Catholics, constituting 5% of the African American population.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Of the total number of Jehovah's Witnesses, 22% are Black.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Historically, between 15 and 30% of enslaved Africans brought to the Americas were Muslims, but most of these Africans were converted to Christianity during the era of American slavery.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Prominent members included activist Malcolm X and boxer Muhammad Ali.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Malcolm X is considered the first person to start the movement among African Americans towards mainstream Islam, after he left the Nation and made the pilgrimage to Mecca.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 1975, Warith Deen Mohammed, the son of Elijah Muhammad took control of the Nation after his father's death and guided the majority of its members to orthodox Islam.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African American Muslims constitute 20% of the total US Muslim population, the majority are Sunni or orthodox Muslims, some of these identify under the community of W.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The Nation of Islam led by Louis Farrakhan has a membership ranging from 20,000 to 50,000 members.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] There is also a small but growing group of African American Jews, making up less than 0.5% of African Americans or about 2% of the Jewish population in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The majority of African-American Jews are Ashkenazi, while smaller numbers identify as Sephardi, Mizrahi, or other.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Many African-American Jews are affiliated with denominations such as the Reform, Conservative, Reconstructionist, or Orthodox branches of Judaism, but the majority identify as "Jews of no religion", commonly known as secular Jews.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] A significant number of people who identify themselves as "Black Jews" are affiliated with syncretic religious groups, largely the Black Hebrew Israelites, whose beliefs include the claim that African Americans are descended from the Biblical Israelites.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Jews of all races typically do not accept Black Hebrew Israelites as Jews, in part because they are usually not Jewish according to Jewish law, and in part because these groups are sometimes associated with antisemitism.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African-American Jews have criticized the Black Hebrew Israelites, regarding the movement as primarily composed of Black non-Jews who have appropriated Black-Jewish identity.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In the 2010s, confirmed atheists were less than one half of one percent, similar to numbers for Hispanics.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2025, a Pew Research Center study found that, among Black Americans, Christian affiliation has declined in recent years.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The share of Black adults identifying as Christian fell from 85% in 2007 to 79% in 2014 and 73% in 2021, mirroring a broader decline in Christianity in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] However, Black adults remain more likely than U.S. adults overall to identify as Christian (73% vs.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] By comparison, about half or fewer adults in other racial or ethnic groups report that religion is very important or that they pray daily, and even smaller shares attend services monthly.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Religiosity among Black Americans also varies by age.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] 39% of Black adults aged 65 and older describe themselves as very religious, compared with 21% of those under 30.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] This age pattern is similar to that observed among White and Hispanic Americans, although Black adults of all ages are more likely than other groups to describe themselves as very religious.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] According to a Gallup survey, 4.6% of Black or African Americans self-identified as LGBT in 2016, while the total portion of American adults in all ethnic groups identifying as LGBT was 4.1% in 2016.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African American women are more likely than African American men to openly identify as LGBT.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The life expectancy for Black men in 2008 was 70.8 years.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Life expectancy for Black women was 77.5 years in 2008.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 1900, when information on Black life expectancy started being collated, a Black man could expect to live to 32.5 years and a Black woman 33.5 years.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 1900, White men lived an average of 46.3 years and White women lived an average of 48.3 years.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African American life expectancy at birth is persistently five to seven years lower than European Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Black men have shorter lifespans than any other group in the US besides Native American men.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Black people have higher rates of obesity, diabetes, and hypertension than the US average.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] For adult Black men, the rate of obesity was 31.6% in 2010.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] For adult Black women, the rate of obesity was 41.2% in 2010.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African Americans have higher rates of mortality than any other racial or ethnic group for eight of the top ten causes of death.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2013, among men, Black men had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by White, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander (A/PI), and American Indian/Alaska Native (AI/AN) men.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Among women, White women had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by Black, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander, and American Indian/Alaska Native women.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African Americans also have higher prevalence and incidence of Alzheimer's disease compared to the overall average.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Black women lead the nation in abortions.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] According to a 2022 report, Black women made up 40% of abortions despite making up 13% of the U.S. woman population.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African Americans are more likely than White Americans to die due to health-related problems developed by alcoholism.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Alcohol abuse is the main contributor to the top three causes of death among African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In December 2020, African Americans were less likely to be vaccinated against COVID-19 due to mistrust in the US medical system.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] From 2021 to 2022, there was an increase in African Americans who became vaccinated.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Still, in 2022, COVID-19 complications became the third leading cause of death for African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Violence is a major problem within the African American community.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] A report from the US Department of Justice states "In 2005, homicide victimization rates for Blacks were more than six times as high as the rates for Whites".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The report also found that "94% of Black victims were killed by Blacks." Of the nearly 20,000 recorded US homicides in 2022, African Americans made up the majority of offenders and victims despite making up less than 15% of the population.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2024, all of the five most dangerous US cities have a significant Black population and highly concerning Black-on-Black violent crime rate.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Black males age 15–44 are the only race/sex category for which homicide is a top-five cause of death.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Black women are three times more likely to be killed by an intimate partner than White women.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Black children are more than three times as likely to die due to parental abuse and neglect than White children.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, African Americans have higher rates of sexually transmitted infections (STIs) compared to Whites, with five times the rates of syphilis and chlamydia, and 7.5 times the rate of gonorrhea.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The disproportionately high incidence of HIV/AIDS among African Americans has been attributed to homophobic influences, lack of condom usage, and lack of proper healthcare.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black men is seven times higher than the prevalence for White men, and Black men are more than nine times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White men.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black women is 20 times higher than White women, and Black women are more than 15 times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White women.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African Americans have several barriers for accessing mental health services.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Counseling has been frowned upon and distant in utility and proximity to many people in the African American community.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2004, a qualitative research study explored the disconnect with African Americans and mental health.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The study was conducted as a semi-structured discussion which allowed the focus group to express their opinions and life experiences.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] The results revealed a couple key variables that create barriers for many African American communities to seek mental health services such as the stigma, lack of four important necessities; trust, affordability, cultural understanding and impersonal services.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Historically, many African American communities did not seek counseling because religion was a part of the family values.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African Americans who have a faith background are more likely to seek prayer as a coping mechanism for mental issues rather than seeking professional mental health services.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2015 a study concluded, African Americans with high value in religion are less likely to utilize mental health services compared to those who have low value in religion.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In the United States, counseling approaches are based on the experience of White Americans and do not fit within the African American culture.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] African American families tend to resolve concerns within the family, and it is viewed by the family as a strength.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] On the other hand, when African Americans seek counseling, they face a social backlash and are criticized.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] They may be labeled "crazy", viewed as weak, and their pride is diminished.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Because of this, many African Americans instead seek mentorship within communities they trust.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Terminology is another barrier in relation to African Americans and mental health.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] There is more stigma on the term *psychotherapy* versus counseling.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In one study, psychotherapy is associated with mental illness whereas counseling approaches problem-solving, guidance and help.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] More African Americans seek assistance when it is called counseling and not psychotherapy because it is more welcoming within the culture and community.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Counselors are encouraged to be aware of such barriers for the well-being of African American clients.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] Without cultural competency training in health care, many African Americans go unheard and misunderstood.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] In 2021, African Americans had the third highest suicide rate trailing American Indians/Alaska Natives and White Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] However, African Americans had the second highest increase of its suicide rate from 2011 to 2021, growing 58%.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p02] As of 2024, suicide is the second leading cause of death among African-Americans between the ages of 15 and 24, with Black men being four times more likely to kill themselves than Black women.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Recent studies of African Americans using genetic testing have found ancestry to vary by region and sex of ancestors.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] These studies found that on average, African Americans have 73.2–82.1% Sub-Saharan African, 16.7–24% European, and 0.8–1.2% Native American genetic ancestry, with large variation between individuals.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Commercial testing services have reported similar variation, with ranges from 0.6 to 2 percent Native American, 19 to 29 percent European, and 65 to 80 percent Sub-Saharan African ancestry.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] According to a genome-wide study by Bryc et al.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] (2009), the mixed ancestry of African Americans in varying ratios came about as the result of sexual contact between West/Central Africans (more frequently females) and Europeans (more frequently males).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] This can be understood as being the result of enslaved African American females being raped by White males.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Consequently, the 365 African Americans in their sample have a genome-wide average of 78.1% West African ancestry and 18.5% European ancestry, with large variation among individuals (ranging from 99% to 1% West African ancestry).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The West African ancestral component in African Americans is most similar to that in present-day speakers from the non-Bantu branches of the Niger-Congo family.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] (2014) observed that around 50% of the overall ancestry of African Americans traces comes from a population similar to the Niger-Congo-speaking Yoruba of southern Nigeria and southern Benin, reflecting the centrality of this West African region in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The next most frequent ancestral component found among African Americans was derived from Great Britain, in keeping with historical records.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] It constitutes a little over 10% of their overall ancestry and is most similar to the Northwest European ancestral component also carried by Barbadians.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] (2009) found a similar proportion of Yoruba-like ancestry in their African American samples, with a minority also drawn from Mandenka and Bantu populations.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Additionally, the researchers observed an average European ancestry of 21.9%, again with significant variation between individuals.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] (2009) note that populations from other parts of the continent may also constitute adequate proxies for the ancestors of some African American individuals; namely, ancestral populations from Guinea Bissau, Senegal and Sierra Leone in West Africa and Angola in Southern Africa.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] An individual African American person can have over fifteen African ethnic groups in their genetic makeup alone due to the slave trade covering such vast areas.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Altogether, genetic studies suggest that African Americans are a genetically diverse people.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] According to DNA analysis led in 2006 by Penn State geneticist Mark D.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] According to Shriver, around five percent of African Americans also have at least 12.5% Native American ancestry (equivalent to one Native American great-grandparent and their forebears).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Research suggests that Native American ancestry among people who identify as African American is a result of relationships that occurred soon after slave ships arrived in the American colonies, and European ancestry is of more recent origin, often from the decades before the Civil War.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Africans bearing the E-V38 (E1b1a) likely traversed across the Sahara, from east to west, approximately 19,000 years ago.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] E-M2 (E1b1a1) likely originated in West Africa or Central Africa.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] According to a Y-DNA study by Sims et al.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] (2007), the majority (≈60%) of African Americans belong to various subclades of the E-M2 (E1b1a1, formerly E3a) paternal haplogroup.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] This is the most common genetic paternal lineage found today among West/Central African males and is also a signature of the historical Bantu migrations.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The next most frequent Y-DNA haplogroup observed among African Americans is the R1b clade, which around 15% of African Americans carry.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] This lineage is most common today among Northwestern European males.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The remaining African Americans mainly belong to the paternal haplogroup I (≈7%), which is also frequent in Northwestern Europe.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] According to an mtDNA study by Salas et al.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] (2005), the maternal lineages of African Americans are most similar to haplogroups that are today especially common in West Africa (>55%), followed closely by West-Central Africa and Southwestern Africa (<41%).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The characteristic West African haplogroups L1b, L2b,c,d, and L3b,d and West-Central African haplogroups L1c and L3e in particular occur at high frequencies among African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] As with the paternal DNA of African Americans, contributions from other parts of the continent to their maternal gene pool are insignificant.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Formal political, economic and social discrimination against minorities has been present throughout American history.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Saito, Associate Professor of Sociology and American Studies & Ethnicity at the University of Southern California, writes, "Political rights have been circumscribed by race, class and gender since the founding of the United States, when the right to vote was restricted to White men of property.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Those who economically gained the most from slavery were the planter class, owners of large-scale plantations where large numbers of enslaved Africans were held captive and forced to produce crops to create wealth for a White elite.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Although they have gained a greater degree of social equality since the civil rights movement, African Americans have remained stagnant economically, which has hindered their ability to break into the middle class and beyond.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] As of 2020, the racial wealth gap between Whites and Blacks remains as large as it was in 1968, with the typical net worth of a White household equivalent to that of 11.5 Black households.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Despite this, African Americans have increased employment rates and gained representation in the highest levels of American government in the post–civil rights era.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] However, widespread racism remains an issue that continues to undermine the development of social status.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Economically, of all the racially Black ethnic groups on the globe, African Americans are the wealthiest and most successful, with one in every fifty African American families being millionaires.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] This equates in 2023 to approximately 1.79 million African American millionaires in the United States, which is more than the number of millionaires in any racially Black country, and many other countries, around the world.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] In the US, which has the largest per-capita prison population in the world, African Americans are overrepresented as the second-largest population of prison inmates (38%) in 2023, coming second to Whites, who made up 57% of the prison population.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] According to the National Registry of Exonerations, Blacks are roughly 7.5 times more likely to be wrongfully convicted of murder in the US than Whites.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] In 2012, the New York City Police Department detained people more than 500,000 times under the city's stop-and-frisk law.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Of the total detained, 55% were African-Americans, while Black people made up 20% of the city's population.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African American males are more likely to be killed by police when compared to other races.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] This is one of the factors that led to the creation of the Black Lives Matter movement in 2013.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] According to *The Guardian*, "The specter of Karen persisted as Black Lives Matter protests and civil unrest spread around the country following Floyd's murder and reckonings with racism began to roil institutions, toppling careers as well as statues".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] In the aftermath of the peak Black Lives Matter protests and widespread police reform efforts in the early 2020s, crime rates surged across the nation, especially in predominantly Black neighborhoods.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Many cities experienced near-record or record levels of violence and other criminal activity.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] As a result, numerous municipalities scaled back police reform initiatives and increased funding for law enforcement.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] After over 50 years, marriage rates for all Americans began to decline while divorce rates and out-of-wedlock births have climbed.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] These changes have been greatest among African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] After more than 70 years of racial parity Black marriage rates began to fall behind Whites.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Single-parent households have become most common, and according to US census figures released in January 2010, only 38% of Black children lived with both their parents.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] In 2021, statistics show that over 80% marriages in the African American ethnic group marry within their ethnic group.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Black children are overrepresented in the U.S. foster care system.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] In 2017, Black American children made up 14% of the children population but 22% of those in the foster care system.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Black American children are more than twice as likely to be placed in foster care than White American children.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The first ever anti-miscegenation law was passed by the Maryland General Assembly in 1691, criminalizing interracial marriage.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] In a speech in Charleston, Illinois in 1858, Abraham Lincoln stated, "I am not, nor ever have been in favor of making voters or jurors of negroes, nor of qualifying them to hold office, nor to intermarry with white people".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] By the late 1800s, 38 US states had anti-miscegenation statutes.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] By 1924, the ban on interracial marriage was still in force in 29 states.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] While interracial marriage had been legal in California since 1948, in 1957 actor Sammy Davis Jr. faced a backlash for his involvement with White actress Kim Novak.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Harry Cohn, the president of Columbia Pictures, with whom Novak was under contract, gave in to his concerns that a racist backlash against the relationship could hurt the studio.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Davis briefly married Black dancer Loray White in 1958 to protect himself from mob violence.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Inebriated at the wedding ceremony, Davis despairingly said to his best friend, Arthur Silber Jr., "Why won't they let me live my life?" The couple never lived together, and commenced divorce proceedings in September 1958.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] In 1967 the law was ruled unconstitutional (via the 14th Amendment adopted in 1868) by the US Supreme Court in *Loving v.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] In 2008, Democrats overwhelmingly voted 70% against California Proposition 8, African Americans voted 58% in favor of it while 42% voted against Proposition 8.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] On May 9, 2012, Barack Obama, the first Black president, became the first US president to support same-sex marriage.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Since Obama's endorsement there has been a rapid growth in support for same-sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] As of 2012, 59% of African Americans support same-sex marriage, which is higher than support among the national average (53%) and White Americans (50%).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Polls in North Carolina, Pennsylvania, Missouri, Maryland, Ohio, Florida, and Nevada have also shown an increase in support for same sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] On November 6, 2012, Maryland, Maine, and Washington all voted for approve of same-sex marriage, along with Minnesota rejecting a constitutional amendment banning same-sex marriage.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Exit polls in Maryland show about 50% of African Americans voted for same-sex marriage, showing a vast evolution among African Americans on the issue and was crucial in helping pass same-sex marriage in Maryland.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Black Americans hold far more conservative opinions on abortion, extramarital sex, and raising children out of wedlock than Democrats as a whole.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] On financial issues, however, African Americans are in line with Democrats, generally supporting a more progressive tax structure to provide more government spending on social services.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African Americans have fought in every war in the history of the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The gains made by African Americans in the civil rights movement and in the Black Power movement not only obtained certain rights for African Americans but changed American society in far-reaching and fundamentally important ways.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Prior to the 1950s, Black Americans in the South were subject to de jure discrimination, or Jim Crow laws.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] They were often the victims of extreme cruelty and violence, sometimes resulting in deaths: by the post World War II era, African Americans became increasingly discontented with their long-standing inequality.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The civil rights movement marked an enormous change in American social, political, economic and civic life.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Over time, it has changed in fundamental ways the manner in which Blacks and Whites interact with and relate to one another.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Some activists and academics contend that American news media coverage of African American news, concerns, or dilemmas is inadequate, or that the news media present distorted images of African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Johnson founded Black Entertainment Television (BET), a network that targets young African Americans and urban audiences in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Over the years, the network has aired such programming as rap and R&B music videos, urban-oriented movies and television series, and some public affairs programs.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] On Sunday mornings, BET would broadcast Christian programming; the network would also broadcast non-affiliated Christian programs during the early morning hours daily.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] According to Viacom, BET is now a global network that reaches households in the United States, Caribbean, Canada, and the United Kingdom.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The network has gone on to spawn several spin-off channels, including BET Her (originally launched as *BET on Jazz*).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Another network targeting African Americans is TV One.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] TV One is owned by Urban One, founded and controlled by Catherine Hughes.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Urban One is one of the nation's largest radio broadcasting companies and the largest African American-owned radio broadcasting company in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] In June 2009, NBC News launched a new website named TheGrio.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] It is the first African American video news site that focuses on underrepresented stories in existing national news.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] From their earliest presence in North America, African Americans have significantly contributed literature, art, agricultural skills, cuisine, clothing styles, music, language, and social and technological innovation to American culture.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The cultivation and use of many agricultural products in the United States, such as yams, peanuts, rice, okra, sorghum, grits, watermelon, indigo dyes, and cotton, can be traced to West African and African American influences.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Notable examples include George Washington Carver, who created nearly 500 products from peanuts, sweet potatoes, and pecans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Soul food is a variety of cuisine popular among African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] It is closely related to the cuisine of the Southern United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The descriptive terminology may have originated in the mid-1960s, when *soul* was a common definer used to describe African American culture (for example, soul music).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African Americans were the first peoples in the United States to make fried chicken, along with Scottish immigrants to the South.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Although the Scottish had been frying chicken before they emigrated, they lacked the spices and flavor that African Americans had used when preparing the meal.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The Scottish American settlers therefore adopted the African American method of seasoning chicken.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] However, fried chicken was generally a rare meal in the African American community and was usually reserved for special events or celebrations.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African-American English is a variety (dialect, ethnolect, and sociolect) of American English, commonly spoken by urban working-class and largely bi-dialectal middle-class African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] It shares parts of its grammar and phonology with the Southern American English dialect.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African American English differs from Standard American English (SAE) in certain pronunciation characteristics, tense usage, and grammatical structures, which were derived from West African languages (particularly those belonging to the Niger–Congo family).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Virtually all habitual speakers of African American English can understand and communicate in Standard American English.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] As with all linguistic forms, AAVE's usage is influenced by various factors, including geographical, educational and socioeconomic background, as well as formality of setting.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Additionally, there are many literary uses of this variety of English, particularly in African American literature.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Other languages are spoken by specific sub-communities.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The Gullah language is an English-based creole language spoken mostly in the coastal regions of South Carolina and Georgia by the Gullah; an off-shoot of this is Afro-Seminole Creole spoken by Black Seminoles mostly now in Mexico and Brackettville, Texas.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Louisiana Creole is a French-based creole and spoken mostly in Louisiana.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African-American names are part of the cultural traditions of African Americans, most of these cultural names having no connection to Africa but strictly an African American cultural practice that developed in the United States during enslavement.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] This new evidence became apparent by census records which show African Americans and White Americans, though they spoke the same language, chose to use different names even during times of enslavement, which is where and when the development of African American cultural names began.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Prior to this newer information, it was only thought that before the 1950s, and 1960s, most African-American names closely resembled those used within European-American culture.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Babies of that era were generally given a few common names, with children using nicknames to distinguish the various people with the same name.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] With the rise of 1960s civil rights movement, there was a dramatic increase in names of various origins.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] By the 1970s, and 1980s, it had become common among African Americans to invent new names for themselves, although many of these invented names took elements from popular existing names.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Prefixes such as La/Le, Da/De, Ra/Re and Ja/Je, and suffixes like -ique/iqua, -isha and -aun/-awn are common, as are inventive spellings for common names.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The book *Baby Names Now: From Classic to Cool—The Very Last Word on First Names* places the origins of "La" names in African-American culture in New Orleans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Even with the rise of inventive names, it is still common for African Americans to use biblical, historical, or traditional European names.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Daniel, Christopher, Michael, David, James, Joseph, and Matthew were thus among the most frequent names for African-American boys in 2013.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The name LaKeisha is typically considered American in origin but has elements that were drawn from both French and West/Central African roots.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Names such as LaTanisha, JaMarcus, DeAndre, and Shaniqua were created in the same way.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Punctuation marks are seen more often within African American names than other American names, such as the names Mo'nique and D'Andre.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African American music is one of the most pervasive African American cultural influences in the United States today and is among the most dominant in mainstream popular music.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Hip-hop, R&B, funk, rock and roll, soul, blues, and other contemporary American musical forms originated in Black communities and evolved from other Black forms of music, including blues, doo-wop, barbershop, ragtime, bluegrass, jazz, and gospel music.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African American-derived musical forms have also influenced and been incorporated into virtually every other popular music genre in the world, including country and techno.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African Americans have also had an important role in American dance.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Jones, a prominent modern choreographer and dancer, has included historical African American themes in his work, particularly in the piece "Last Supper at Uncle Tom's Cabin/The Promised Land".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Likewise, Alvin Ailey's artistic work, including his "Revelations" based on his experience growing up as an African American in the South during the 1930s, has had a significant influence on modern dance.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Another form of dance, stepping, is an African American tradition whose performance and competition has been formalized through the traditionally Black fraternities and sororities at universities.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Discussions of race and sports in the United States, where the two subjects have always been intertwined in American history, have focused to a great extent on African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Depending on the type of sport and performance level, African Americans are reported to be over- or under-represented.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African Americans compose the highest percentage of the minority groups active at the professional level, but are among those who show the lowest participation overall.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] And though the list of African Americans in professional sports remains high, it only represents a small fraction of aspiring black athletes.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Many African American authors have written stories, poems, and essays influenced by their experiences as African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African American literature is a major genre in American literature.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Famous examples include Langston Hughes, James Baldwin, Richard Wright, Zora Neale Hurston, Ralph Ellison, Nobel Prize winner Toni Morrison, and Maya Angelou.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African American inventors have created many widely used devices in the world and have contributed to international innovation.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Norbert Rillieux created the technique for converting sugar cane juice into white sugar crystals.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Moreover, Rillieux left Louisiana in 1854 and went to France, where he spent ten years working with the Champollions deciphering Egyptian hieroglyphics from the Rosetta Stone.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Most slave inventors were nameless, such as the slave owned by the Confederate President Jefferson Davis who designed the ship propeller used by the Confederate navy.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] By 1913, over 1,000 inventions were patented by Black Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Among the most notable inventors were Jan Matzeliger, who developed the first machine to mass-produce shoes, and Elijah McCoy, who invented automatic lubrication devices for steam engines.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Granville Woods had 35 patents to improve electric railway systems, including the first system to allow moving trains to communicate.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Morgan developed the first automatic traffic signal and gas mask.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Lewis Howard Latimer invented an improvement for the incandescent light bulb.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] More recent inventors include Frederick McKinley Jones, who invented the movable refrigeration unit for food transport in trucks and trains.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Lloyd Quarterman worked with six other Black scientists on the creation of the atomic bomb (code named the Manhattan Project) and helped develop the first nuclear reactor.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] As part of the preservation of their culture, African Americans have continuously launched their own publications and publishing houses, such as Robert Sengstacke Abbott, founder of the Chicago Defender newspaper, and Carter G.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Woodson, the founder of Black History Month who spent over thirty years documenting and publishing African American history in journals and books.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The Johnson Publishing Company, founded by John H.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Johnson in 1942, is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The term *African American* was popularized by Jesse Jackson in the 1980s, although there are recorded uses from the 18th and 19th centuries, for example, in post-emancipation holidays and conferences.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Earlier terms also used to describe Americans of African ancestry referred more to skin color than to ancestry.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Other terms (such as *colored*, *person of color*, or *negro*) were included in the wording of various laws and legal decisions which some thought were being used as tools of White supremacy and oppression.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] A 16-page pamphlet entitled "A Sermon on the Capture of Lord Cornwallis" is notable for the attribution of its authorship to "An *African American*".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Published in 1782, the book's use of this phrase predates any other yet identified by more than 50 years.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] In the 1980s, the term *African American* was advanced to give descendants of American slaves, and other American Blacks who lived through the slavery era, a heritage and a cultural base.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The term was popularized in Black communities around the country via word of mouth and ultimately received mainstream use after Jesse Jackson's use in 1988.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Subsequently, major media outlets adopted it.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Surveys in the 1990s and the first decade of the 21st century showed that the majority of Black Americans had no preference for *African American* versus *Black American*, although they had a slight preference for the latter in personal settings and the former in more formal settings.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] By 2021, according to polling from Gallup, 58% of Black Americans expressed no preference for what their group should be called, with 17% each preferring *Black* and *African-American*.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] In 2023, the government released a new more detailed breakdown due to the rise in racially Black immigration into the US, listing African American as a compound termed ethnicity, distinguished from other racially Black ethnicities such as Nigerian, Jamaican etc.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The term *African American* embraces pan-Africanism as earlier enunciated by prominent African thinkers such as Marcus Garvey, W.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The term *Afro-Usonian*, and variations of such, are more rarely used.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] In preparation for the 2010 US census, a marketing and outreach plan called *2010 Census Integrated Communications Campaign Plan* (ICC) recognized and defined African Americans as Black people born in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] From the ICC perspective, African Americans are one of three groups of Black people in the United States: African Americans, Black Africans, and Afro-Caribbeans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The ICC plan was to reach the three groups by acknowledging that each group has its own sense of community that is based on geography and ethnicity.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The best way to market the census process toward any of the three groups is to reach them through their own unique communication channels and not treat the entire Black population of the US as though they are all African Americans with a single ethnic and geographical background.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Historically, "race mixing" between Black and White people was taboo in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] So-called anti-miscegenation laws, barring Blacks and Whites from marrying or having sex, were established in colonial America as early as 1691, and endured in many Southern states until the Supreme Court ruled them unconstitutional in *Loving v.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The taboo among American Whites surrounding White-Black relations is a historical consequence of the oppression and racial segregation of African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Harvard University historian Henry Louis Gates Jr. wrote in 2009 that "African Americans...are a racially mixed or mulatto people—deeply and overwhelmingly so".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] After the Emancipation Proclamation, Chinese American men married African American women in high proportions to their total marriage numbers due to few Chinese American women being in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] African slaves and their descendants have also had a history of cultural exchange and intermarriage with Native Americans, although they did not necessarily retain social, cultural or linguistic ties to Native peoples.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] There are also increasing intermarriages and offspring between non-Hispanic Blacks and Hispanics of any race, especially between Puerto Ricans and African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Racially mixed marriages have become increasingly accepted in the United States since the civil rights movement.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] A Gallup poll conducted in 2013 found that 84% of Whites and 96% of Blacks approved of interracial marriage, and 87% overall.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Black men are more than twice as likely to date and marry interracially than Black women.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] At the end of World War II, some African American military men stationed in Asia and Europe impregnated local non-Black women, resulting in the birth of thousands of mixed-race children called "Brown Babies".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Some of these families later immigrated to the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] However, some mixed-race children, especially in Japan, were placed in orphanages due to social stigmas associated with half-Black fatherless children in the 1950s.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Author Debra Dickerson has argued that the term *Black* should refer strictly to the descendants of Africans who were brought to America as slaves, and not to the sons and daughters of Black immigrants who lack that ancestry.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Thus, under her definition, President Barack Obama, who is the son of a Kenyan, is not Black.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] "Lumping us all together", Dickerson wrote, "erases the significance of slavery and continuing racism while giving the appearance of progress." Similar comments have been made concerning Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican immigrant, who was elected vice president in 2020.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The American Descendants of Slavery (ADOS) movement coalesces around this view, arguing that Black descendants of American slavery deserve a separate ethnic category that distinguishes them from other Black groups in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Their terminology has gained popularity in some circles, but others have criticized the movement for a perceived bias against (especially poor and Black) immigrants, and for its often inflammatory rhetoric.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Politicians such as Obama and Harris have received especially pointed criticism from the movement, as neither are ADOS and have spoken out at times against policies specific to them.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Most notably, Malcolm X and Kwame Ture expressed similar views that African Americans are Africans who "happen to be in America", and should not claim or identify as being American if they are fighting for Black (New Afrikan) liberation.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Historically, this is due to the enslavement of Africans during the transatlantic slave trade, ongoing anti-Black violence, and structural racism in countries like the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Before the independence of the Thirteen Colonies until the abolition of slavery in 1865, an African American slave was commonly known as a *negro*.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] *Free negro* was the legal status in the territory of an African American person who was not enslaved.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The term was used until the second quarter of the 20th century, when it was considered outmoded – although it was retained in the name of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) – and generally gave way again to the exclusive use of *negro*.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] By the 1940s, the term was commonly capitalized (*Negro*); but by the mid-1960s, it was considered disparaging.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] By the end of the 20th century, *negro* had come to be considered inappropriate and was rarely used and perceived as a pejorative.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The term is rarely used by younger Black people, but remained in use by many older African Americans who had grown up with the term, particularly in the Southern US.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The term remains in use in some contexts, such as the United Negro College Fund, an American philanthropic organization.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] There are many other deliberately insulting terms, many of which were in common use (e.g., *nigger*), but had become unacceptable in normal discourse before the end of the 20th century.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] One exception is the use, among the Black community, of the slur *nigger* rendered as *nigga*, representing the pronunciation of the word in African American English.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] This usage has been popularized by American rap and hip-hop music cultures and is used as part of an in-group lexicon and speech.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] It is not necessarily derogatory and, when used among Black people, the word is often used to mean "homie" or "friend".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] Acceptance of intra-group usage of the word *nigga* is still debated, although it has established a foothold among younger generations.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-american-p03] The NAACP denounces the use of both *nigga* and *nigger*.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] When Spanish and French explorers reached the region in the 16th century, they encountered numerous tribes of Native Americans, with the Cherokees and the Catawba people being the most prominent prior to the arrival of African American slaves in South Carolina.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The initial European efforts to establish settlements were unsuccessful; however, in 1670, a lasting English settlement was founded along the coast close Charleston.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The English then began dependent on African American slavery.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Enslaved Africans first arrived in the area that would become South Carolina in 1526 as part of a Spanish expedition from the Caribbean.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In 1670 when the British Empire colonized the region, the Lords Proprietor established the Province of Carolina and created a plantation-style economy that increasingly relied on enslaved labor.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] By 1708, the enslaved African population in South Carolina exceeded the number of free whites.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] This black majority existed in the state until the Great Migration in the early twentieth century, with some temporary fluctuations.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Black people were present at the founding of the English colony in South Carolina.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Europeans brought black slaves to the state after the genocide of Native Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Unlike her more northern colonies, South Carolina's introduction to slavery was based largely on a preexisting enslavement system from the Caribbean in the late seventeenth century.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Many of the colony's first white settlers immigrated from Barbados.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] By 1700, South Carolina's system of slavery resulted in the development of the rice and indigo cash crop industry.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Contrary to popular understanding, cotton was not a big factor until the early 1800s.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] By the eighteenth century, most of the slave trade in South Carolina was under the control of the Royal African Company, established by the British monarchy to facilitate trading in west Africa.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Slave traders typically offered products such as iron and copper bars, brass pans and kettles, cowry shells, old guns, gunpowder, cloth, and alcohol in return for African slaves; ships typically loaded between 200 and over 600 slaves.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Charleston, South Carolina, named Charles Town in colonial times, was a major global port for trading goods and slaves.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] More than half of the slaves that came to British North America passed through Charles Town.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] By 1770, more than 3,000 African slaves were imported to the city annually.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The International African American Museum, opening in 2022, is being built in Charleston, South Carolina, on the site where Gadsden's Wharf, the disembarkation point of up to 40% of all American slaves, once stood.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] When slaves arrived in the city, they were often inspected and auctioned at the local market.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Potential buyers inspected male slaves for characteristics of strength.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] If a male slave appeared weak, old, or frail, he sold for a lower price than a young, brawny male.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Slaves with bruising and scaring from whippings were auctioned more cheaply because buyers were uneasy about purchasing a slave they believed to be rebellious.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Women were inspected for characteristics of beauty and child reproduction.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Both male and female slaves were inspected for diseases, typically being stripped of their clothing.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Some potential buyers even forced open the mouths of slaves to view their teeth, another method of inspecting for disease.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Slaves that were not purchased in Charles Town were forced to travel to other slave auction houses, such as in Georgetown or in other colonies.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Slave auctions also served as a form of entertainment for many white residents in Charles Town.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Even people that had no intentions of bidding on a slave watched as African men and women were sold by the auctioneer.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In some instances, auctioneers provided wine, drink and other forms of refreshments for slave buyers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] As the slave practice grew, the prices of slaves rose.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] By the 1770s, slaves sold as high as $1,500, or about the price of a new car in modern times, and families were often separated through the auction.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Most of South Carolina's slaves were imported from the Angola-Congo region, Senegambia and Sierra Leone.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The Stono Rebellion was the largest slave uprising in the British mainland colonies, resulting in the deaths of 40-50 Africans and 23 colonists.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The revolt was led by a slave named Jemmy in 1739, who gathered 22 slaves near the Stono River in Charleston.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] They marched chanting "Liberty," and recruited more slaves along the way.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The group killed two storekeepers to gather weapons and ammunition.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The slaves' goal was to march to Spanish Florida, a well-known refuge for escapees.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Lieutenant Governor William Bull warned slave owners that a rebellion was forming; the slave owners gathered militia to suppress the uprising.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The following day, the slaves and militia met, and after the confrontation, 23 whites and 47 slaves were killed.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] While the slave rebellion was defeated, it encouraged many governments in British America to pass laws further restricting the freedoms of slaves and of free blacks.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In response to the Stono Rebellion, the South Carolina legislature passed more laws limiting the rights of African Americans and more-strictly regulating the institution of slavery.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] One such law was the Negro Act of 1740, which restricted slave assembly, education, and movement in addition to requiring legislative approval for each act of manumission.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The act established penalties for slave owners who were too lenient in punishing their slaves.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The act required slaves to travel with a pass and gave any white male the ability to scrutinize, question, and detain blacks they believed to be escaped slaves.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Politicians were divided on how African Americans who fought for the American cause should be rewarded.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Two delegates to the Continental Congress, Edward Rutledge and Thomas Lynch, sought to bar free African Americans from enlisting in the militia, while other statesmen, such as Henry Laurens, favored exchanging military service for freedom.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Under Lauren's proposal, the Continental Congress would provide slave owners $1,000 for each able-bodied slave under 35 years-old provided for military service, though this proposal was rejected.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Another proposal from Thomas Sumter stated that any man who joined the militia for ten months would be gifted one free slave, though this proposal was also rejected.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Ultimately, slaves who served as Patriots were returned into slavery following the war's conclusion.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] African Americans who served in the Continental Army were mostly laborers or cooks, and very few fought in combat situations.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Slaves did not typically serve non-voluntarily; most were commanded by their slave owners to serve in their stead, and any slave who refused to serve after being instructed, risked a penalty of death.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] If the slave was paid the typical daily wage of seven pence, by law, that money belonged to the slave owner.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Some South Carolina African Americans fought for the British as Loyalists.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Dunmore's Proclamation declared that any slave who ran away from his master and joined the royal forces would be granted his freedom.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] This promise was never carried out since the British lost the war.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] As many as 25,000 slaves, along with other British Loyalists, escaped South Carolina following the conclusion of the war.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] One band of three hundred Georgia and South Carolina slaves, who called themselves King of England's Soldiers, fled to the Savannah River swamps and survived until May 1786 when they were burned out by militia.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves was signed by President Thomas Jefferson in 1807.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Anticipating the enforcement of this law, Charleston traders acquired approximately 70,000 Africans between 1804 and 1807.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] For most of the nineteenth century, slaves in South Carolina were born into slavery, not carried from Africa.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] By 1860, the slave population of South Carolina was just over 402,000, and the free black population was just over 10,000.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] At the same time, there were approximately 291,000 whites in the state, accounting for about 30% of the population.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Compared to other states, South Carolina had a very large population of slaves, which had nearly quadrupled in the 70 years between 1790 and 1860.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Much of this growth can be attributed to the rise of the cotton industry.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Prior to the 1800s, South Carolina's slave-based economy dealt mostly in the harvesting of tobacco, rice, and indigo.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In 1800, the Santee Canal connected the Santee and Cooper rivers, making it possible to transport goods directly from Columbia, South Carolina to Charleston by water.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The creation of the Santee Canal, coupled with the invention of the cotton gin, transformed the cotton-production business into part of the global economy.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The upcountry of South Carolina had fertile land that supported the growing of short-staple cotton, and many planters ruined the fertility of the land, often unknowingly, by planting season after season of cotton.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] But the slave-driven cotton industry catapulted South Carolina as one of the wealthiest locations on Earth by the mid-nineteenth century.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Slavery soon spread throughout all of South Carolina instead of having a concentration along the coast as it had since the 1600s.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The expansion of slavery throughout the state led to the full maturity of the slave society in South Carolina, and by 1860, 45.8 percent of white families in the state owned slaves, giving the state one of the highest percentages of slaveholders in the country.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Denmark Vesey was born into slavery in St.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Vesey's owner settled in Charleston after the Revolutionary War.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Vesey won $1,500 prize in a city lottery; he used $600 to purchase his freedom.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] After gaining his freedom, Vesey socialized with many slaves and became increasingly set on helping them escape slavery.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In 1821, Vesey and a few slaves began to conspire to plan a revolt.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In order for the revolt to be successful, Vesey had to recruit others and strengthen his army, which was not complicated because he was a lay preacher.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Vesey inspired slaves by connecting their potential freedom to the biblical story of the Exodus.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] He planned the insurrection to take place on Bastille Day, July 14, 1822.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Vesey held numerous secret meetings and eventually gained the support of both slaves and free blacks throughout the city and countryside who were willing to fight for their freedom.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Vesey planned to make a coordinated attack on the Charleston arsenal.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] After seizing weapons, Vesey intended to commandeer ships from the harbor and sail to Haiti, which had recently led a successful slave revolution.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Vesey and his followers also planned to kill white slaveholders throughout the city, as had been done in Haiti, and liberate more slaves.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Two slaves loyal to their masters, George Wilson and Joe LaRoche, opposed Vesey's planned revolution; they reported the scheme to officials.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Wilson and LaRoche's testimonies confirmed an earlier report from another slave named Peter Prioleau.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Based on the slaves' warning, the city launched a search for conspirators.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The Mayor James Hamilton organized a citizens' militia, putting the city on alert.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] White militias and groups of armed men patrolled the streets daily for several weeks until many slaves were arrested, including Vesey.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Over the course of five weeks, the city court ordered the arrest of 131 black men, charging them with conspiracy.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In total, the courts convicted 67 men of conspiracy and hanged 35, including Vesey, in July 1822.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] A total of 31 men were deported, 27 reviewed and acquitted, and 38 questioned and released.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] While a failed revolution, Vesey's conspiracy resulted in stricter slave laws and regulations against blacks to be enacted throughout the country.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Policing and control of the freedmen and slave populations was stepped up even further in the aftermath of the Charleston Workhouse Slave Rebellion of 1849.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In Antebellum South Carolina, slave-owning society was divided into three tiers: the Yeomen class, which on average owned 1-5 slaves; the Middling class, which on average owned 5-20 slaves; and the Planter class, which on average owned over 20 slaves.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] While some slaves worked on huge planter-class plantations, some slaves worked on small farms.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The planter class only accounted for 12% of slave owners.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Life as a slave varied drastically from owner to owner.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Typically, there were three types of slave labor structures in South Carolina: (1) the gang system, which was the most common and required slaves to work from sun up to sundown.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] This system was most commonly used on cotton plantations and was the most brutal; (2) the task system, which required slaves to complete a certain task by the end of the workday.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] This system, while less common, provided slaves time to exercise their culture if their tasks were completed early; (3) household slaves, who were typically females that worked inside the slaveowner's home chiefly to nursery children, prepare food and cook.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Slaves were often prohibited from gathering, practicing religion, learning to read or write, and owning weapons, though much of these restrictions were decided by the slave owner.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Whites that hit, harmed, or otherwise punished slaves were generally protected in South Carolina.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Rules and regulations passed under the Negro Act of 1740 carried both into South Carolina law and custom.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] For example, if a white man were to kill a slave, he would be subject to a misdemeanor and fined.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In reverse, if a black man were to kill a white man, he would be executed.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Slaves that attempted to run away from their masters were subject to various types of punishments ranging from whipping, the most common, to death.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Some slaves were branded with a hot iron or had part of their bodies marked.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Some slave owners took a knife to a slave's ear or nose and disfigured it in a way that distinguished the slaves as runaways.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Some slaves were tortured by having salt, vinegar, or pepper seeds fleshed into their wounds.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Some rebellious slaves were sold away from their families.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Female slaves, especially aged 14–25, were exposed to the risk of being raped by a white man.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Owners of female slaves could freely and legally use them as sexual objects.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Furthermore, females of breeding age were often kept pregnant, as slavery status was inherited through the mother and following the bans on importing new slaves from Africa, it was the most abundant source of new slaves.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Any black man found having sexual relations with a white woman would have been put to death.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Slaves in South Carolina exercised culture through cuisine, music, dance, hair, language, and religion.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Many slaves sang songs about escaping, such as Follow the Drinking Gourde and Wade in the Water.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] African Americans in the coastal regions of South Carolina, commonly referred to as the "Gullah," are known for preserving more of their African heritage than any other community in the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] David Drake, an enslaved man from Edgefield, South Carolina, became famous for his pottery creations.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Historians estimate that Drake produced over 40,000 pieces throughout his lifetime.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] While Drake was living, his pottery was worth about fifty cents apiece, though some pieces in the twenty-first century have sold for as high as $50,000.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Drake often inscribed poetry or messages onto his pottery.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Many of these inscriptions verged on sedition and rebellion since it was generally prohibited for slaves to read or write.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In one inscription, Drake wrote "I wonder where is all my relations / Friendship to all—and every nation." Drake was likely attempting to subtly criticize the institution of slavery.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] For a seventeen-year period, Drake did not sign any pots, likely because his owner prohibited it.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The free black population of South Carolina never exceeded 2% of the overall population.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The developing economies of Northern and upper-South states facilitated abolition while the heavy investment in King Cotton in South Carolina only strengthened the institution of slavery.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] By 1860, the free black population of South Carolina remained at 2% while Maryland's was nearly 49%.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] It was uncommon for slaves to be freed in the state since manumission was generally illegal.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In 1850, for instance, only two slaves gained their freedom.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Of the small percentage of free blacks in South Carolina, 79% of those were mulattos or people of mixed race.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Some slaveowners had children by their slaves, and such offspring were more likely to be manumitted, or freed, than those fully of African descent.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Most free blacks lived in the countryside as small farmers, but a small percentage worked as artisans, tenant farmers, or acquired their own land.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Other free blacks held slaves for their labor.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Daria Thomas, a planter in Union District in the 1860s, used many of his 21 slaves on his cotton farm.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Likewise, William Ellison used 63 slaves on his plantation and in his cotton gin manufacturing business in Sumter.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Most freed blacks, however, struggled because of legal disabilities.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Since 98% of the state's population was enslaved, free blacks consistently had to prove that they were free.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In the early 1800s, freed blacks were still tried in slave courts, and often faced an all-white jury.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Free blacks could not testify in court against whites, and they were often prohibited from entering many businesses or establishments.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Free blacks over the age of fifteen were required to be escorted by a white guardian.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] These restriction laws became stronger as slave rebellions across the nation drove fearful whites to attempt to stop further insurrection movements.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] According to Walter Edgar, a South Carolina historian, no evidence suggests that African Americans fought for the South during the Civil War.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Confederates often feared arming blacks.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Some slaves assisted with the Confederate army, but black men were not legally allowed to serve as combat soldiers in the Confederate Army—they were cooks, teamsters, and manual laborers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Also, they were usually compelled by force to serve.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Many slaves across the South took advantage of the war to escape to freedom.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] These escapees were sometimes referred to by the Union as "contrabands" as in confiscated enemy property.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Composed of free African Americans from New England, some of whom were former slaves and fugitive slaves, the 54th Massachusetts Infantry Regiment fought at the Second Battle of Fort Wagner in Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Fort Wagner was among the most heavily fortified Confederate forts, and on July 18, 1863, the 54th Massachusetts charged the fort.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The battle lasted nearly three hours, and over 1,500 Union soldiers were captured, killed, or wounded.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Although a tactical defeat, the publicity of the battle of Fort Wagner led to further action for black U.S. troops in the Civil War, and it spurred additional recruitment that gave the Union Army a further numerical advantage in troops over the South.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Robert Smalls was born into slavery in 1839 in Beaufort County.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] When he was 12, Smalls' master sent him to Charleston to hire out as a laborer for a $1 weekly wage, with the rest of the wage being paid to his master.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Smalls worked first at a hotel, then as a lamplighter; he later worked at the docks where he became a longshoreman, a rigger, a sailmaker, and eventually a wheelman.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] As a result, he was very knowledgeable about Charleston harbor.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In the fall of 1861, Smalls was assigned to steer the CSS Planter, a lightly armed Confederate military transport.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The Planter's duties were to deliver dispatches, troops and supplies, to survey waterways, and to lay mines.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] On the evening of May 12, the *Planter* was docked as usual at the wharf below General Ripley's headquarters.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Its three white officers disembarked to spend the night ashore, leaving Smalls and the crew on board, "as was their custom." (Afterward, the three Confederate officers were court-martialed and two convicted, but the verdicts were later overturned.) At about 3 a.m.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] May 13, Smalls and seven of the eight slave crewmen made their previously planned escape to the Union blockade ships.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Smalls put on the captain's uniform and wore a straw hat similar to the captain's.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] He sailed the *Planter* past what was then called Southern Wharf and stopped at another wharf to pick up his wife and children and the families of other crewmen.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Smalls guided the ship past the five Confederate harbor forts without incident, as he gave the correct signals at checkpoints.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The *Planter* had been commanded by a Captain Charles C.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Relyea and Smalls copied Relyea's manners and straw hat on deck to fool Confederate onlookers from shore and the forts.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The *Planter* sailed past Fort Sumter at about 4:30 a.m.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The alarm was only raised after the ship was beyond gun range.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Smalls headed straight for the Union Navy fleet, replacing the rebel flags with a white bed sheet which was brought by his wife.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The *Planter* had been seen by the USS *Onward*, which was about to fire until a crewman spotted the white flag.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Smalls, having just turned 23, quickly became known in the North as a hero for his daring exploit.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Newspapers and magazines reported his actions.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Congress passed a bill awarding Smalls and his crewmen the prize money for the *Planter* (valuable not only for its guns but low draft in Charleston bay); Southern newspapers demanded harsh discipline for the Confederate officers whose joint shore leave had allowed the slaves to steal the boat.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Smalls's share of the prize money came to US$1,500 (equivalent to $48,375 in 2025).
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Smalls was made pilot of the Crusader under Captain Alexander Rhind.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In June of that year, Smalls was piloting the Crusader on Edisto in Wadmalaw Sound when the Planter returned to service, and an infantry regiment engaged in the Battle of Simmon's Bluff at the head of the Edisto River.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] He continued to pilot the Crusader and the Planter.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] As a slave, he had assisted in laying mines (then called "torpedoes") along the coast and river.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Now, as a pilot, he helped find and remove them and serviced the blockade between Charleston and Beaufort.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] After the Civil War, Smalls became the founder of the Republican Party of South Carolina.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] As a Republican, he was elected as a U.S.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Representative to Congress five times, and he served in the South Carolina Senate.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Laws passed during the Reconstruction era, including the Thirteenth, Fourteenth, and Fifteenth amendments to the United States Constitution greatly expanded the rights of African Americans in South Carolina.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In 1867, U.S. troops registered voters in South Carolina, including for the first time, African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Many former Confederates and Southern Democrats boycotted the voting process, leading to a high Republican turnout in the election the following year.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Consequentially, in the 1868 election the following year, Republicans won elections in a landslide.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The newly elected legislative branch of South Carolina, the General Assembly, was majority African American.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] As instructed by President Andrew Johnson, the new legislature began creating a new constitution that was not going to resurrect the old South.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The new constitution provided representation according to population, rather than by population and wealth, as the formula in place previously had done.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] It eliminated property qualifications for voting and guaranteed universal male suffrage.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The Constitution of 1868 was the first South Carolina constitution that required a "uniform system of free public schools throughout the State".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] It legalized interracial marriages and barred the public accommodation of public facilities; any person violating anti-segregation laws was required to forfeit his business license and pay a $1,000 fine, and be imprisoned for up to five years at hard labor.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Black codes in South Carolina were a series of laws meant to prevent African Americans of civil liberties.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Black codes applied only to "persons of color," defined as including anyone with more than one eighth, or 12.5% "Negro blood." Below are some examples of Black codes passed by the South Carolina General Assembly.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The enforcement of black codes was an effort by the Democrats and white supremacists to maintain a system of racial inequality and hierarchy that existed before the Civil War.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Black codes, in addition to poll taxes, literacy tests, and intimidation meant that the Democratic party in South Carolina was virtually unopposed until the Civil Rights Movement in the 1950s.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Between the mid-1870s and the early 1970s, African Americans were largely unable to vote in South Carolina.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Though the Fifteenth amendment protected black men's right to vote, poll taxes, literacy tests, and intimidation from groups like the Ku Klux Klan meant that African American turnouts for elections were extremely low.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] By 1940, African American voters accounted for only 0.8 percent of those of voting age in the state.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] South Carolina required voters to complete a voter application in order to vote.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The test was highly arbitrary; the examiner, almost always a white male, could deny anyone the ability to vote based on his judgment alone.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] For example, if a man read the entire South Carolina constitution, but mispronounced one word, the examiner could still refuse the voter access to the polling facility.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The state of South Carolina asserted that poll taxes were not voting qualifications but instead a method of funding public schools, though historians and scholars today dispute this claim.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In 1923, South Carolina's poll tax was $1.00, or approximately $15 in 2020 dollars.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] After the Civil War, many African Americans worked farming jobs as sharecroppers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In the 1920s, the average weekly wage of a sharecropper was between $5 and $6.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The $1.00 poll tax would have accounted for approximately one day's wage, or 20% of one week's wage.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Toward the end of Reconstruction, African Americans were discouraged from voting through intimidation and violence.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The Ku Klux Klan, or KKK, was one of the most prominent terrorist groups in the state that emerged in the 1870s.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In 1871, evidence emerged that African Americans were being murdered or terrorized by the Klan; in York County alone, eleven African Americans were murdered and 600 were whipped.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Governor Robert Scott refused to declare martial law or combat the violence of the Klan.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Grant signed the Ku Klux Klan Act, which made it a federal crime to prevent any American citizens from exercising their rights.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In nine South Carolina counties, Grant declared martial law and arrested approximately 600 Klansmen; 53 pleaded guilty and five were convicted at trial.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Temporarily, the number of incidents of lynching and terrorism significantly reduced but increased again after the Compromise of 1877 in which President Hayes removed federal troops from the South.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Klan activity in South Carolina was much more predominant in the upstate where the African American population was not as heavy.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Between 1882 and 1968, there were 4,743 reported lynching in South Carolina.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Many historians, however, reject the validity of this number, asserting that as many as 60% of lynchings were unreported or undocumented.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The majority of victims killed or abused by the Klan were Republican African Americans, though some Republican whites suffered the same fate in smaller numbers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] A group with similar motives to the Ku Klux Klan was the Red Shirts.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The *1876 South Carolina Red Shirts Battle Plan* stated: "Every Democrat must feel honor bound to control the vote of at least one Negro, by intimidation...In speeches to Negroes you must remember that they can only be influenced by their fears, superstitions and cupidity.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Treat them so as to show them you are the superior race and that their natural position is that of subordination to the white man." The Red Shirts were less secretive than the KKK, working more openly, but both organizations had the same goal: return Democrats to power.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Ferguson* (1896) decision, race-based segregation was legal across the United States, though such separation had already rooted itself in South Carolina's culture and custom.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In a 1900 speech on the floor of the United States Senate, one of South Carolina U.S.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Senators, Benjamin Tillman said: "We of the South have never recognized the right of the negro to govern the white man, and we never will.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] We have never believed him to be equal to the white man, and we will not submit to his gratifying his lust on our wives and daughters without lynching him.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Beginning in the late 1870s, Democrats repealed most of the laws passed by Republicans during the Reconstruction era, thus revoking civil liberties and rights from South Carolina African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] For instance, an 1879 miscegenation statute prohibited interracial marriages, stating "Marriage between a white person and an Indian, Negro, mulatto, mestizo, or half-breed shall be null and void." This law was not overturned until the *Loving v.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In 1895, the General Assembly created a new constitution, which required "No children of either race "shall ever be permitted to attend a school provided for children of the other race." An 1898 statue required that railroad companies provide separate cars for white and colored passengers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] A similar statue in 1905 required the segregation of streetcars.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] State and municipal codes prohibited whites and blacks from eating in the same portion of a restaurant, using the same public facilities (such as drinking fountains or bathrooms), and required segregated seating.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] A 1952 state code compelled cotton textile manufacturers to prohibit different races from working together in the same room or from using the same exits or bathrooms.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Another 1952 statue made it a crime for any colored person to adopt or take custody of a white child.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Likewise, African Americans struggled to enter the workforce in skilled positions.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Many African Americans worked as sharecropped, in which they made little money.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Factories and business owners often favored white employees over black employees, and if black employees were hired, they were typically paid less than whites.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In 1896, Lucy Hughes Brown became the first female African American physician in the state.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] She co-founded the Hospital and Training School for Nurses in 1897 with Alonzo Clifton McClennan, an African American doctor.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Cultural rules in Jim Crow South Carolina also kept African Americans in a position of inferiority.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] For example, a South Carolina customed required African Americans to address whites in certain ways: "If you are white, never say 'Mr.', 'Mrs.', 'sir', or 'ma'am' to nonwhites and always call them by their first names.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] If you are nonwhite, always say 'Mr.', 'Mrs.', 'sir', or "ma'am" to whites and never call them by their first name." These unwritten rules prohibited whites and blacks from shaking hands and required blacks to remove hats when speaking to whites.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Failure to abide by these rules could lead to blacks being arrested, whipped, or lynched.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Federal reforms meant to help African Americans were mostly lost.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The Freedmen's Bureau was largely ineffective, and the 13th, 14th, and 15th amendments to the U.S.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Constitution were denied to African Americans.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In Charleston, after five white men at the Charleston Naval Shipyard felt that they had been cheated by a black man, they searched for him.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Unable to find him, they attacked African Americans at random.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] One of the men they attacked, Issac Doctor, fired in self-defense.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Word quickly spread about the shooting and, within an hour, over 1,000 white sailors and a few white citizens gathered in the city street.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The white sailors raided shooting galleries and stole firearms.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The mob marched around the city attacking African Americans and their businesses and homes.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The riot was controlled by police by 2:30 a.m., three and one-half hours after its start.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Consequentially, 6 African Americans died, 17 suffered serious injuries, and 35 were admitted to hospitals.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Seven white sailors and one police officer were seriously injured, and eight sailors were admitted to hospitals.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Lacking evidence, police arrested 49 men accused of inciting a riot, but the charges were dropped.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] 8 received $50 fines for unlawful weapon possession.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The Great Migration was the movement of 6 million African Americans out of the rural Southern United States to the urban Northeast, Midwest, and West that occurred between 1916 and 1970.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In 1900, South Carolina's African American population was approximately 58%, a majority.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] By 1970, the population decreased to 30%.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Throughout the 1930s and 1940s, African Americans in South Carolina continued to live in segregated neighborhoods, attend segregated schools, and utilize segregated public facilities.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Many young African American men, either voluntarily or by the draft, went to Europe and the South Pacific after the Bombing of Pearl Harbor to fight the Axis.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The military remained segregated until President Harry Truman signed an executive order after World War II to integrate the armed forces.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] While all servicemen faced difficulties and tribulations during their time in the military, African Americans faced greater challenges.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Bura Walker was a black enlisted soldier who was promoted to the rank warrant officer at Fort Jackson, a rank which very few African Americans achieved.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Because of the state's segregation laws, Walker could not move into the officer quarters because his fellow officers were all white.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Many black veterans recalled that they were treated more poorly by officers than white soldiers and were not respected by their fellow enlistees.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] African Americans who remained in South Carolina still struggled to participate in the political process and were often denied the ability to work skilled jobs.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The Charleston Naval Yard, which employed mostly white men before the war, saw a large increase in the number of female and African American workers during World War II.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] More than 6,000 blacks were hired by the Naval Yard, though when the war was over, white veterans were usually favored over black employees.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In summer of 1942, many rumors spread that black citizens were stockpiling war materials in Charleston, convincing the mayor to cancel the annual black Labor Day parade.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Another Charleston resident remembers seeing two African Americans attempt to sit at the front of a city bus, something strictly prohibited by the Jim Crow laws of the time.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] When the bus driver told them to move back they seemed to hesitate.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] At that, the driver pulled out a pistol and ordered the two African Americans to the rear, and they quickly complied and no further incident occurred.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Like much of the nation during the 1950s and 1960s, African Americans in South Carolina led peaceful and nonviolent protests against unfair segregation laws.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] However, much of the national spotlight during the civil rights movement focused on Alabama and Mississippi.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Much of the civil rights movement in South Carolina happened without many riots or violence, except in a few cases.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In Greenville, the Greenville Eight consisted of African American college students sitting protesting the segregated library system by entering the white-only branch.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In Columbia, black students at Allen University and Benedict College led protests throughout the city.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In Orangeburg, South Carolina, students at South Carolina State University and Claflin University led protests and marches to challenge desegregation.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Throughout the 1950s and 1960s, many businesses, institutions, and governments resisted integration.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Senator Strom Thurmond of South Carolina authored the Southern Manifesto, which denounced the 1954 *Brown v.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Board* decision as "unwarranted" and referred to anti-segregationists as "agitators and troublemakers invading our States." Many school districts ignored the *Brown v.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] Board of Education* decision in 1954; some districts were still segregated into the 1970s.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] In 1972, Governor John Carl West signed the Human Affairs Law, creating the South Carolina Human Affairs Commission.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p01] The Commission is tasked with investigation, mediating, and litigating claims of racial and other forms of discrimination in employment, housing, and public services.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] In 1993, Jim Clyburn was elected to the U.S.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] House of Representatives from South Carolina's 6th congressional district.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Clyburn served as the House Majority Whip from 2007 to 2011, and from 2019 to 2023.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] In 2012, Governor Nikki Haley appointed U.S.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Representative Tim Scott to fill the vacancy created by Jim DeMint's resignation.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Scott became the first African American man to serve on the U.S.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Scott won the 2014 special election, and won reelection in 2016.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Benjamin became the first African American mayor of Columbia.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] In 2006, Terence Roberts became the first African American mayor of Anderson.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] In 2015, Barbara Blain-Bellamy became the first African American female mayor in the state in Conway.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] In December 2019, Barry Walker became the first African American mayor of Irmo.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Burgess became the first African American mayor of North Charleston.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] As of 2020, 44 of 172 members of the South Carolina General Assembly were African American, accounting for about 26%.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] In the 2016 Presidential Election African Americans in South Carolina chiefly voted for the Democratic Party.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] According to a CNN exit poll, 94% of voting African Americans voted for Hillary Clinton, while 4% voted for Donald Trump, who carried the state's nine electoral votes.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] According to 2017 census estimates, African Americans account for 27.3% of South Carolina's population, a number which has been steadily declining since the beginning of the twentieth century.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Many blacks leaving South Carolina are now recently moving to other Southern cities with more job opportunities including Atlanta, Charlotte, Dallas, Houston, Raleigh and San Antonio.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] According to the 2010 census, of the 46 counties in South Carolina, there are 12 that have a majority-black population.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] On June 17, 2015, Dylann Roof, a 21-year-old white supremacist, entered Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church and attended Bible study with 12 others.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Near the end of the lesson, Roof said pointed a gun at one of the church members and said, "I have to do it.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] You rape our women and you're taking over our country.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] And you have to go." Roof fired, killing nine and wounding three.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Among those dead was South Carolina Senator Clementa C.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Roof reportedly shouted racial slurs as he carried out the shooting.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Roof attempted to commit suicide but ran out of ammunition.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] He was arrested the following day in Shelby, North Carolina.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Roof later admitted that he was led by racist motives to kill Pinckney and others at the church, and he chose the Emanuel church in particular because it is one of the oldest in South Carolina, founded in 1817.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] In December 2016, a jury convicted Roof of 33 counts of hate crime and murder charges.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] In 2017, he was sentenced to death for these charges.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Dylann Roof had posted many images of himself on social media boasting a Confederate Flag, the same flag that flew on the South Carolina Statehouse grounds.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] After the shooting, calls to remove the Confederate flag from the Statehouse grounds intensified, including from influential figures such as President Barack Obama, Mitt Romney, and Jeb Bush.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] On June 20, three days after the shooting, several thousand people gathered at the Statehouse to protest the flag's display.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Bree Newsome, an African American civil rights activist, was arrested for scaling the flag pole and removing the flag, though it was replaced within the hour.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Counter-protesters at the Statehouse, though fewer in number, advocated keeping the flag on the grounds.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] The flag had been added to the Statehouse dome during the Civil Rights Movement in the early 1960s.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] In 1996, Republican Governor David Beasley advocated to remove the flag, a stance that contributed to his failure to win reelection against Democrat Jim Hodges.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] In 2000, the flag was removed from the Statehouse dome to a location on the grounds where it stood until 2015.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Republican Governor Nikki Haley called for the flag's removal, stating, "We are not going to allow this symbol to divide us any longer." Other national figures endorsed Haley's decision, including Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell and Texas Governor Rick Perry.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] On June 26, the state senate voted 103–10 to remove the flag, and by the House, 94–20.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Haley signed the bill, and the flag was removed on July 10 and added to the South Carolina Confederate Relic Room & Military Museum.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] On April 4, 2015, Walter Scott was shot in the back by a police officer in North Charleston.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] The officer, Michael Slager, stopped Scott because of a non-functioning third brake light.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] The video from Slager's dashcam shows him approaching Scott's car, speaking to Scott, and then returning to his patrol car.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Scott exited his car and fled with Slager giving chase on foot.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Scott fled and Slager fired eight rounds; Scott was struck from the rear five times.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] The mayor of North Charleston ordered that every police officer in the city would be required to wear a body camera, and the South Carolina Senate allocated $3.4 million to be used for body cams within the state.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] National leaders, such as the Reverend Al Sharpton, encouraged charges to be brought up against the police officer.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] The Black Lives Matter movement protested Scott's death.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Slager said that he "felt threatened" by Scott, but ultimately, Slager was charged with murder and was subsequently sentenced to 20 years in prison.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] After the murder of George Floyd in Minneapolis, Minnesota on May 25, 2020, protests erupted across the United States.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] In South Carolina, protests were mostly peaceful.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Many of the largest cities imposed curfews following a day of violence throughout the state.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Several businesses and restaurants in downtown Columbia were vandalized.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Protesters torched three police cruisers and unsuccessfully attempted to burn down several buildings.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] In Charleston, protesters stopped traffic on Interstate-26.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] On June 14, 2020, thousands marched from Martin Luther King Park in Five Points to the Statehouse in Columbia.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] The march was a tribute to the Million Man March led by in Washington, D.C. in 1995.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] According to Leo Jones, the event's organizer, the goal of the march was to protest racial injustice and was an extension of the George Floyd protests that had occurred in the prior weeks.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Marchers were encouraged to wear their "Sunday best" and to register to vote after the march if unregistered.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Tents were set up on the Statehouse grounds that allowed people to register to vote.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Benjamin, Richland County Sheriff Leon Lott, and Columbia Police Chief Skip Holbrook participated in the march.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/african-americans-in-south-carolina-p02] Additionally, groups that supported the march were 100 Black Men, and the NAACP.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Andrew Young was born on March 12, 1932, in New Orleans, to Daisy Young, a schoolteacher, and Andrew Jackson Young, a dentist.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young's father hired a professional boxer to teach Andrew and his brother to defend themselves.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In a 1964 interview with author Robert Penn Warren for his book, *Who Speaks for the Negro?,* Young recalls the tensions of segregation in New Orleans, especially growing up in a fairly well-to-do household.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He recalls his parents trying to "compensate for segregation" by providing for their children but were reluctant to help less wealthy black communities in the area.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young attended Dillard University for one year before graduating from Howard University.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He then earned a divinity degree from Hartford Seminary in Hartford, Connecticut, in 1955.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He is a member of Alpha Phi Alpha fraternity.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young was appointed to serve as pastor of a church in Marion, Alabama.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] It was there in Marion that he met Jean Childs, who later became his wife.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young became interested in Mahatma Gandhi's concept of nonviolent resistance as a tactic for social change.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He encouraged African Americans to register to vote in Alabama, and sometimes faced death threats while doing so.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] It was at this time that he became a friend and ally of Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 1955, Young accepted a pastorate at Bethany Congregational Church in Thomasville, Georgia.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 1957, Young and Jean moved to New York City when he accepted a job with the Youth Division of the National Council of Churches.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] While in New York City, Young regularly appeared on *Look Up and Live*, a weekly Sunday morning television program on CBS, produced by the National Council of Churches in an effort to reach out to secular youth.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young served as a pastor of the Evergreen Congregational Church in Beachton, Georgia, from 1957 to 1959.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 1960, he joined the Southern Christian Leadership Conference.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] No longer satisfied with his work in New York City, Young moved to Atlanta, Georgia, in 1961 upon the invitation of Bernard Lafayette and worked to register black voters.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young played a key role in the 1963 events in Birmingham, Alabama, serving as a mediator between the white and black communities as they negotiated against a background of protests.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 1964, Young was named executive director of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] As a colleague and friend of Martin Luther King Jr., he was a strategist and negotiator during the Civil Rights Campaigns in Birmingham (1963), St.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He was jailed for his participation in civil rights demonstrations, both in Selma, Alabama, and in St.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] The movement gained congressional passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young was with King in Memphis, Tennessee, when King was assassinated in 1968.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 1970, Andrew Young ran as a Democrat for the 5th District seat in the US House of Representatives, from Georgia, but was unsuccessful.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Bennette Jr. introduced him to Murray M.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Silver, an Atlanta attorney, who served as his campaign finance chairman.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He later was re-elected in 1974 and in 1976.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] During his four-plus years in Congress, he was a member of the Congressional Black Caucus, and was involved in several debates regarding foreign relations, including the decision to stop supporting the Portuguese attempts to hold on to their colonies in southern Africa.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young also sat on the powerful Rules Committee and the Banking and Urban Development Committee.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young opposed the Vietnam War, helped enact legislation that established the U.S.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Institute for Peace, established the Chattahoochee River National Recreation Area and negotiated federal funds for MARTA and the Atlanta Highways.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 1977, President Jimmy Carter appointed Young to serve as the United States Ambassador to the United Nations.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young was the first African American to hold the position.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Atlanta city councilman Wyche Fowler won the special election to fill Young's seat in Congress.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Although the US and the UN enacted an arms embargo against South Africa, as President Carter's UN ambassador, Young vetoed economic sanctions.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In response, US Representative Larry McDonald (D-GA) sponsored a resolution to impeach Young, but the measure failed 82 to 293.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 1979, Young played a leading role in advancing a settlement in Rhodesia with Robert Mugabe and Joshua Nkomo, who had been two of the rebel leaders in the Rhodesian Bush War, which had ended in 1979.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] The settlement paved the way for Mugabe to take power as Prime Minister of the newly formed Republic of Zimbabwe.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] There had been a general election in 1979, bringing Bishop Abel Muzorewa to power as leader of the United African National Council leading to the short-lived country of Zimbabwe Rhodesia.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Though majority rule had been implemented, many in the international community felt that the reforms were not wide-ranging enough.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young refused to accept the election results and described the election as "neofascist," a sentiment echoed by United Nations Security Council Resolution 445 and 448.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] The situation was resolved the next year with the Lancaster House Agreement and the establishment of Zimbabwe.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young's favoring of Mugabe and Nkomo over Muzorewa and his predecessor and ally, Ian Smith, has been controversial.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Many African-American activists, including Jesse Jackson and Coretta Scott King, supported the anticolonialism represented by Mugabe and Nkomo.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] However, it was opposed by others, including civil-rights leader Bayard Rustin, who argued that the 1979 election had been "free and fair", as well as Senators Harry F.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] It was later criticized in 2005 by Gabriel Shumba, executive director of the anti-Mugabe Zimbabwe Exiles Forum.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In July 1979, Young discovered that an upcoming report by the United Nations Division for Palestinian Rights called for the creation of a Palestinian State.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young wanted to delay the report because the Carter Administration was dealing with too many other issues at the time.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He met with the UN representatives of several Arab countries to try to convince them the report should be delayed; they agreed in principle but insisted that the Palestine Liberation Organization also had to agree.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] As a result, on July 20, Young met with Zuhdi Labib Terzi, the UN representative of the PLO, at the apartment of the UN Ambassador from Kuwait.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] On August 10, news of the meeting became public when the Mossad leaked its illegally-acquired transcript of the meeting first to Prime Minister Menachem Begin, and then through his office to *Newsweek*.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] The meeting was highly controversial since the United States had already promised Israel that it would not meet directly with the PLO until it recognized Israel's right to exist.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] During the controversy, Young took a break and was invited by John F.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Kennedy Jr. to speak about apartheid in South Africa at Brown University.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young's UN ambassadorship ended on August 14.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Carter denied any complicity in what was called the "Andy Young Affair" and asked Young to resign.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Asked about the incident by *Time* soon afterward, Young stated, "It is very difficult to do the things that I think are in the interest of the country and maintain the standards of protocol and diplomacy....
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] After his ambassadorship ended, Young became a guest lecturer at Michigan State University in East Lansing, Michigan.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 1981, after being urged by a number of people, including Coretta Scott King, the widow of Martin Luther King Jr., Young ran for mayor of Atlanta.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He was elected later that year with 55% of the vote, succeeding Maynard Jackson.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] As mayor of Atlanta, he brought in $70 billion of new private investment.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He continued and expanded Jackson's programs for including minority and female-owned businesses in all city contracts.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] The Mayor's Task Force on Education established the Dream Jamboree College Fair that tripled the college scholarships given to Atlanta public school graduates.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 1985, he was involved in renovating the Atlanta Zoo, which was renamed Zoo Atlanta.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young was re-elected as mayor in 1985 with more than 80% of the vote.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Atlanta hosted the 1988 Democratic National Convention during Young's tenure.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He was prohibited by term limits from running for a third term.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] A 1993 survey of historians, political scientists and urban experts conducted by Melvin G.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Holli of the University of Illinois at Chicago saw Young ranked as the fifteenth-best American big-city mayor to serve between the years 1820 and 1993.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] The survey also saw Young ranked the fifth-best big-city mayor to serve in office post-1960.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] After leaving the mayor's office in early 1990, Young launched a bid for the Democratic nomination for governor in 1990.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He ran in a primary that included three former or future governors of Georgia: then lieutenant governor Zell Miller, then-state senator Roy Barnes, and former governor Lester Maddox.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] The field also contained then state representative Lauren "Bubba" McDonald.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] The first poll put Young at 38 percent to Miller's 30 percent, 15 percent for Maddox and 10 percent for Barnes with McDonald trailing at 7 percent.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young campaigned hard but by the primary, with no central message, his campaign ran into trouble against the well-heeled and prepared lieutenant governor.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Miller led the primary with 40 percent to Young's 29 percent and 21 percent for Barnes, Maddox got 7 percent and McDonald rounded out at 3 percent.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Future U.S. senator Johnny Isakson won the Republican nomination.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] After Miller's stunning and broad-based primary win, Young's campaign floundered.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Many think he failed in his effort by trying to garner support amongst rural, conservative white voters, rather than turning out his urban and African-American base.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Also, Young never found an issue that roused supporters, unlike Miller, who won voters by championing a state lottery.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Miller won the runoff, 2 to 1 and ended Young's gubernatorial aspirations for good.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young has been a director of the Drum Major Institute for Public Policy, and is also the chairman of the board for the Global Initiative for the Advancement of Nutritional Therapy.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 1990, Young was a member of the Atlanta Olympic bid committee.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He served as co-chair of the 1996 Summer Olympic Games.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] From 2000 to 2001, Young served as president of the National Council of Churches.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In April 2000, Young appeared on stage with Vice President Al Gore at Morehouse College as the presidential candidate called for programs to better the access of computers and the Internet for minorities.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] After the election, in which Gore lost to George W.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 2003, Young founded the Andrew Young Foundation, an organization meant to support and promote education, health, leadership and human rights in the United States, Africa and the Caribbean.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] From February to August 2006, Young served as the public spokesman for Working Families for Walmart, an advocacy group for the retail chain Walmart.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young resigned from the position soon after a controversial interview with the *Los Angeles Sentinel*, in which, when asked about Walmart hurting independent businesses, he replied, "You see those are the people who have been overcharging us, and they sold out and moved to Florida.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] I think they've ripped off our communities enough.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 2007, GoodWorks Productions released the documentary film *Rwanda Rising*, about Rwanda's progress since the Rwandan genocide of 1994.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young also served as the film's narrator.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] *Rwanda Rising* premiered as the opening night selection at the Pan African Film Festival in Los Angeles in 2007.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] An edited version of *Rwanda Rising* served as the pilot episode of *Andrew Young Presents*, a series of quarterly, hour-long specials airing on nationally syndicated television.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] On January 22, 2008, Young appeared as a guest on the television show *The Colbert Report*.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Host Stephen Colbert invited Young to appear during the writers' strike, because, in 1969, Young and Colbert's father had worked together to mediate a hospital workers' strike.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young made another appearance on *The Colbert Report* on November 5, 2008, to talk about the election of Barack Obama to the presidency.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 2014, the Tourism office of the Bahamas commissioned Jamaal Rolle to paint a portrait of Andrew Young to give him as a gift during a conference where he was the special guest.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] On January 19, 2015, Young gave the keynote address at Vanderbilt University's Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] The theme was "Dismantling Segregation: Race, Poverty, and Privilege", and Young spoke about his experiences in Selma, stories of traveling with King, and his advice to the next generation of leaders.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young served on the board of the Trumpet Awards Foundation and was a cofounder of Bounce TV, which acquired the Trumpet Awards in 2016.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] On May 13, 2019, Young gave the keynote address at Emory University's spring commencement ceremony.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] On May 29, 2020, Young remarked on the protests in Atlanta in reaction to the murder of George Floyd.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] He stated that riots, violence, and looting "hurt the cause instead of helping it".
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Park along with National Monuments Foundation president Rodney Mims Cook Jr.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] This peace park is located in the Vine City neighborhood on Atlanta's westside and has a strong civil rights focus.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In 2023, Young launched the "Andrew Young HBCU Scholarship Program" funded by McGraw Hill Education in partnership with the Institute of World Politics Chair of Law and Human Rights, Matthew Daniels and the Thurgood Marshall College Fund.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] The scholarship is awarded to students who "demonstrate the vision and leadership potential to be an ambassador for the unifying, non-violent principles of Dr.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] King and Ambassador Young, rooted in respect for the fundamental dignity, rights, and equality of all human beings." Young also endorsed a companion bible study for those seeking to apply Dr.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] King's teachings to improving their communities.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Following a reading from the Book of Ephesians, Young delivered the homily at the state funeral service for Jimmy Carter at Washington National Cathedral on January 9, 2025.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] On March 1, 2026, Young traveled to South Carolina to speak with University of South Carolina Upstate's Bennie Harris for the monthly *Below the Line* feature.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] On March 2, 2026, Young spoke at a private memorial service for Rev.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Jesse Jackson at the South Carolina State House in Columbia, South Carolina.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] On March 22, 2026, Young spoke at the funeral service of civil rights activist Bernard Lafayette, held at Tuskegee University Chapel in Tuskegee, Alabama.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young criticized the Roberts Court's decision in *Louisiana v.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Callais* (2026) for striking down part of Section 2 of the Voting Rights Act.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young has four children with his first wife, Jean Childs Young, who died of liver cancer in 1994.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] His mother-in-law was Idella Jones Childs.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] His daughter Lisa died on March 14, 2025, from cancer.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] In September 1999, Young was diagnosed with prostate cancer which was successfully removed with surgery in January 2000.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Rollins Jr. in the 1978 television miniseries *King*.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/andrew-young] Young is played by Andre Holland in the 2014 film *Selma*.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] CST, Martin Luther King Jr., an American civil rights activist, was fatally shot at the Lorraine Motel in Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Joseph's Hospital, where he was pronounced dead at 7:05 p.m. at age 39.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] The alleged assassin, James Earl Ray, an escaped convict from the Missouri State Penitentiary, was arrested on June 8, 1968, at London's Heathrow Airport, extradited to the United States and charged with the crime.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] On March 10, 1969, Ray pleaded guilty and was sentenced to 99 years in the Tennessee State Penitentiary.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] He later made many attempts to withdraw his guilty plea and to be tried by a jury, but was unsuccessful, before he died in 1998.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] The King family and others believe that the assassination was the result of a conspiracy involving the U.S. government, the mafia, and Memphis police, as alleged by Loyd Jowers in 1993.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] In 1999, the family filed a wrongful death lawsuit against Jowers for the sum of $10 million.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] During the trial, both sides presented evidence alleging a government conspiracy.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] The accused government agencies could not defend themselves or respond because they were not named as defendants.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Based on the evidence, the jury concluded that Jowers and others were "part of a conspiracy to kill King" and awarded the family the symbolic $100 they requested in damages.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] The allegations and the finding of the Memphis jury were later disputed by the United States Department of Justice in 2000 due to a perceived lack of evidence.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] The assassination was one of four major assassinations of the 1960s in the United States, coming several years after the assassination of John F.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Kennedy in 1963 and the assassination of Malcolm X in 1965, and two months before the assassination of Robert F.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] As early as the mid-1950s, Martin Luther King Jr. had received death threats because of his prominence in the civil rights movement.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] He had confronted the risk of death, including a nearly fatal stabbing in 1958, and made its recognition part of his philosophy.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] He taught that murder could not advance the struggle for equal rights.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] After the assassination of President Kennedy in 1963, King told his wife, Coretta Scott King, "This is what is going to happen to me also.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] King traveled to Memphis, Tennessee, in support of striking African-American city sanitation workers.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] At the time, Memphis paid black workers a wage of just $1 an hour.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] There were also no city-issued uniforms, no restrooms, no recognized union, and no grievance procedure for the numerous occasions on which they were underpaid.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] These unethical conditions were imposed by mayor Henry Loeb, and during his tenure, conditions did not significantly improve.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] This, along with the deaths of two workers in a garbage-compacting truck on February 1, 1968, caused laborers to conspire to stage a protest on February 11, 1968.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] The strike took place the following day, and lasted for over two months.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] After being contacted by Reverend James Lawson Jr., King would fly out to Memphis on March 18 to help the strikers, and announced that he would head a march in a few days.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] King and Reverend Ralph Abernathy, a colleague and friend of his, then began this peaceful march at the Clayborn Temple.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] 6,000 people participated in this march, but it would end in violence.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] King was deeply upset by the failure of the march, and left Memphis the following day, but would return along with Abernathy and administrative assistant Bernard Scott Lee on April 3, although their flight had been delayed due to a bomb threat.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] King then checked into room 306 at the Lorraine Motel at about 11:20 a.m., before leaving shortly past 12 p.m. to go to a meeting, announcing that he would head another march on April 5.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] By that time, tornado warnings had been reported that afternoon, and heavy rainfall hit the city by that night.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Despite the weather, King managed to arrive in time to make a planned speech to a gathering at the Mason Temple (also known as the world headquarters of the Church of God in Christ), where around 2,000 people were waiting for him.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] At the Mason Temple on the night of April 3, King delivered his famous "I've Been to the Mountaintop" speech, which soon proved to be his last.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] King had initially asked Abernathy to speak for him, but after seeing the enthusiasm of the crowd at the temple, Abernathy called King and urged him to address the people instead, to which he agreed.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] During the speech, he recalled his 1958 attempted assassination, noting that the doctor who treated him had said that because the knife used to stab him was so close to his aorta, any sudden movement, even a sneeze, might have killed him.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] He referred to a letter written by a young girl who told him that she was happy that he had not sneezed.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] After the night of April 3 went into April 4, King's brother, A.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] King, checked into room 201 at the Lorraine Motel at roughly 1 a.m. after coming from Florida.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] After King woke up, Walter Bailey, the owner of the Lorraine Motel at the time, later stated that King seemed particularly happy that day.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] King, a regular smoker, had gone out to the balcony to smoke a cigarette, a habit he hid from the public.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] King then went to a SCLC (Southern Christian Leadership Conference) staff meeting that morning, and the march that was organized to occur on April 5 was moved to Monday, April 8.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] After the meeting, Abernathy and King had lunch at about 1 p.m., before Abernathy took a nap, and King went to visit his brother to talk with him.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] At roughly 4 p.m., Abernathy was woken up from his nap by the telephone in his motel room, where King asked Abernathy to join them.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] After entering room 201, the three men talked for about an hour, before they returned to their room at about 5 p.m., and King informed Abernathy that they were going to Reverend Billy Kyles' to have dinner.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] They then shaved and dressed for the occasion, and Abernathy told King that he would not be able to attend the poor people's march later that month.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] In response to this, King told Abernathy that he would consider not going to Washington without him, and attempted to call Reverend Nutrell Long to see if he could handle the revival instead, but was unable to reach him.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] By 5:30 p.m., Abernathy had agreed to go to Washington with King, before Kyles came into room 306, urging them to hurry up, as they were leaving soon.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] At about 5:55 p.m., King and Abernathy exited room 306, ready for dinner.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] King then teased his friend Jesse Jackson about being improperly dressed, and paused on the balcony of room 306 to chat with those in the courtyard below, including his driver, Solomon Jones.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Jones then advised King to put on a topcoat, as it was cool outside.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] King's last words were to musician Ben Branch, who was scheduled to perform that night at a planned event.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] King said, "Ben, make sure you play 'Take My Hand, Precious Lord' in the meeting tonight.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Samuel Kyles, who was standing several feet away, King was leaning over the balcony railing in front of room 306 when a single shot rang out.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] At 6:01 p.m., King was struck in the right cheek by a single .30-06 bullet fired from a Remington Model 760 rifle.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] The bullet broke his jaw before lodging in his right shoulder.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] The sheer force of the bullet ripped King's necktie off, before he fell backward diagonally onto the balcony.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Andrew Young was one of the first to tend to King, and while he initially believed he was dead, he found King still had a pulse.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Shortly afterwards, King's head was placed on a pillow, his neck wound was covered with a towel, and a blanket was draped over his torso.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Additionally, photographer Joseph Louw, who was waiting to cover the next part of King's campaign, was staying at room 309 on the day of the assassination.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] At about 6 p.m., Louw was watching the television in his room, when he heard what initially sounded like a loud noise.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Louw then ran out, and saw that King had been shot.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] He was the only photographer in the area, and soon thereafter went back into his room to retrieve his cameras, taking several pictures of the scene.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] About two minutes after the shooting occurred, it was radioed to police, who were stationed across the street.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] At 6:09 p.m., King was lifted onto a stretcher, and placed into an ambulance, being escorted by several police officers on motorcycles.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] At about 6:15 p.m., King arrived in Room 1 of St.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Joseph's Hospital, still unconscious, but alive.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Joseph's, Ted Gaylon was the first to examine King's condition and soon determined that King was still alive.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] However, Gaylon found that King only had a weak pulse and his breathing pattern was irregular.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Despite the large wounds on his face and neck, he was not bleeding excessively, likely because of hypovolemic shock.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Surgeons John Reisser and Rufus Brown soon joined the attempt to save King's life, and managed his airway by 6:18 p.m.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] By 6:22 p.m., Jerome Barrasso joined to help with a tracheostomy, before taking over the resuscitation attempt at 6:30 p.m. alongside neurosurgeon Fredrick Gioia.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Fifteen minutes later, King's blood pressure became undetectable, and the electrocardiogram showed an agonal rhythm.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] After consulting Joe Wilhite and Julian Fleming, it was determined that King showed "no signs of life." Several more attempts to save King's life were made, but his electrocardiogram flatlined and his pupils became fixed.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Barrasso pronounced King dead at 7:05 p.m.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] King's widow, Coretta, had difficulty informing her children that their father was dead.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] For some, King's assassination meant the end of the strategy of nonviolence.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Others in the movement reaffirmed the need to carry on King's and the movement's work.
[src:1969-charleston-hospital-strike/assassination-of-martin-luther-king-jr] Leaders within the SCLC confirmed that they would carry on the Poor People's Campaign that year despite the loss of King.
